Tickets_Subject: Looker Backend Data (System Activity) is slow to query
Ticket_Comment_Body:
I did some research on that Airbyte thing:


1. I was not aware of any exporting possibility (even after I spend a couple of hours researching for a never-launched-product called Looker Lens)
2. Airbyte has no listed Issues in their GH repo about their Looker connector ( https://github.com/airbytehq/airbyte/issues?q=is%3Aissue+looker )
3. Airbyte is using singer under the hood to connect to the source systems (https://github.com/singer-io/tap-looker/blob/master/tap_looker/client.py & https://github.com/airbytehq/airbyte/issues/6164)
4. It seems that this Singer Tap is using the Looker 3.1 API by default and does not support any newer versions (https://github.com/singer-io/tap-looker/blob/fb1f830d4d4a83cbe5cf8f4e563d28171f02caaf/tap_looker/client.py#L11 )
5. However, Looker deprecated the Looker 3.1 API (https://developers.looker.com/api/advanced-usage/version-3x-deprecation )
6. I opened a ticket, but since their code has not been touched for two years, I don't expect to see any changes soon. (https://github.com/singer-io/tap-looker/issues/10 )

Tickets_Subject: Re: [gCRE] Sales Engineering Support, Looker Follow Up - narvar
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Miray Kurtay,

Here is a summary of our hour and a half working session today. Please, pass this on as you see fit.

Problem: Some scheduled Looks, but not all, are being killed by the SFTP server with a Looker generated error (paraphrased) remote host killed connection due to timeout.

Database: PostgreSQL 9.6 (default timeout is 30s but if the db is killing the query, I think we would get a SQL error in Looker, which we are not. I think the SFTP server is killing the query but I could be wrong (if the SFTP timeout is NULL, default is also 30s).

**1ST Recommendation: We should increase both the SFTP and database timeout limits to AT LEAST 300s.**

Investigation: We see the same timeout errors in the looker instance admin/scheduled_jobs and confirmed:


1. Same error
2. Multiple users
3. Different frequencies
4. 40s timeouts

So, we picked one Look that was failing and observed:


1. No results returned
2. No database or LookML errors
3. No LookML errors in the model or view files
4. No unusual or complex LookML (weird syntax, extends, etc)

We opened the Explore of the Look:


1. Removed each of the fields, one at a time, reran the query, no results even for only field
2. Start over, removed the `-1`row limit (Looker hack to have no row limit in the Explore), no results
3. Start over, removed one of the two filters, RESULTS
4. Start over, removed the other filter, RESULTS

NOTE: Next time, start with the filters.

**So, now we know the problem is in the JOIN in the SQL generated by Looker IF the Look SHOULD generate results as defined.**

We identified the JOIN in the model file creating this behavior:


    explore: Returns_Model { from: return_process_info label: "Returns Model (QA)" description: "Returns Order and Item Information" #cancel_grouping_fields: [order_info.order_number,order_info_items.product_sku,order_info_items.id,Returns_Model.return_tracking_number,order_info.created_date,Returns_Model.created_date,Returns_Model.return_tracking_delivery_date,return_reason_codes.retailer_reason_code,return_reason_codes.display_name,Returns_Model.refund_option,return_process_items.user_comments] join: return_process_items { type: left_outer sql_on: ${return_process_items.return_process_info_id} = ${Returns_Model.id} ;; relationship: many_to_one }


This is where I think there might be a problem: this left_outer join with a many_to_one relationship. There are five more JOINs in the model file.

**My working theory is the relationships between these tables is not what is represented in the LookML model file.**

Again, since there is no LookML or SQL errors, these relationships in the model file could be defined correctly and these queries are legitimately returning no results. However, given the number of people experiencing the same problem we should have a plan to reach a resolution.

I asked Miray to put me in touch with the Looker Admin/Developer that created this model file because I am not familiar with the customers underlying schema. I did not want to randomly test JOIN type and relationship values, hoping to get lucky. Better to work with the customer who understands their data more than I ever will.

**2ND Recommendation: We should review the model file to verify JOINs match the underlying schema.**

Here's the plan if we need to execute 2ND option:


1. Work with Dina Care Looker developer to update model
2. Verify changes by running Look to generate expected results
3. Verify other failing Looks are using same or different model file
4. Run Looks to verify they will run successfully when scheduled
5. Identify technical debt if any

SQL and LookML attached.

/dion


Dion Edge (dion@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Central America).

Google BDR got a request for a Looker Demo. The initial meeting will focus on qualification, lead by the Looker rep, but the customer did share some criteria. It would be helpful to the conversation to have an Engineer on hand as backup:

I have a short list of minimum requirements for a solution. While this list will likely grow as we finish collecting business and technical requirements from our internal stakeholders, I want to share it now in the hopes of saving both of us some time.

-

Externally hosted. Multi-tenant is fine, though we’ll likely need to engage our security team if that’s the case.

-

Embed capabilities. The reports can be embedded into our product so it looks like it’s part of the site.

-

A seamless login experience for the user. The login process can be integrated with our application’s login to provide single sign-on so the client doesn’t need to log into our site and then log into the reporting tool.

-

Row-level security so we can build a single report and have it automatically filter to different clients based on who is viewing it.

-

Highly customizable. At minimum, we can use custom color palettes and fonts. We want the reporting to look like a fully integrated part of our product.

-

Easy administration. The chosen solution needs to scale for basic needs (normal turnover in client contacts needing new access) and for anticipated growth (adding new seats).

* * *

Tickets_Subject: We have a strange error when we execute SQL Query.
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Nick,

I think you need to set Database Time Zone and Query Time Zone on connection parameters. Those are needed for any date conversions like in your WHERE clause. Please see the following:


## Database Time Zone
The time zone in which your database stores time-based information. Looker needs to know this so that it can convert time values for users, making it easier to understand and use time-based data. See the Using time zone settings documentation page for more information.


## Query Time Zone
The **Query Time Zone** option is visible only if you have disabled **User Specific Time Zones**.
When **User Specific Time Zones** are disabled, the **Query Time Zone** is the time zone that displays to your users when they query time-based data, and the time zone into which Looker will convert time-based data from the **Database Time Zone**.
See the Using time zone settings documentation page for more information.

Please, let me know how this goes.
Thank you.

/dion

Hi Team,



based on the documentation to sending/scheduling formats I see 3 formats are supported:



The **Format** field contains a drop-down menu of available formats:

- **CSV zip file**: The unformatted data from the dashboard delivered as a collection of comma-separated values (CSV) files in a zipped directory. For deliveries to email, the ZIP file is delivered as an email attachment.
- **PDF**: An image of the dashboard as a single PDF file. The default layout displays tiles as they are arranged in the dashboard, but other layout and sizing options are available under **Advanced options**. For deliveries to email, the file is delivered as an email attachment.
- **PNG visualization**: An image of the dashboard as a single PNG file. The default layout displays tiles as they are arranged in the dashboard, but other layout options are available under **Advanced options**. For deliveries to email, the image appears inline within the body of the email.

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Rupal,

1. adding me here https://<your-looker-instance>.cloud.looker.com/admin/next/users/add with the "View" role should be sufficient I believe
2. I just mean that you could define your combined field in your view definition in LookML, instead of as a Custom Measure. E.g see below for a self-contained example. I don't know what your actual logic is, so I am showing a contrived example:


    connection: "arianplaygroundbq"explore: derived_email_information { join: collection_assignment_master_case { sql_on: ${derived_email_information.sent_date} = ${collection_assignment_master_case.date} ;; }}view: derived_email_information { derived_table: { sql: SELECT "2022-01-01" AS sent_date, "hello" as a UNION ALL SELECT "2022-01-02", "howdy";; } dimension: sent_date { type: date sql: ${TABLE}.sent_date ;; } dimension: a { type: string sql: ${TABLE}.a ;; } measure: count_hello_world { type: number sql: COUNTIF(${a} || ", " || ${collection_assignment_master_case.b} = "hello, world");; }}view: collection_assignment_master_case { derived_table: { sql: SELECT "world" AS b, "2022-01-01" as date UNION ALL SELECT "peeps", "2022-01-01" UNION ALL SELECT "everybody", "2022-01-02";; } dimension: b { type: string sql: ${TABLE}.b ;; } dimension: date { type: date sql: ${TABLE}.date ;; }}


Sincerely,
Arian

Tickets_Subject: Window Function in Looker View
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi there - can you please assign this to Dion, who is familiar with my project?



I am looking to add a window function to this query, that sums up the cumulative total for the date range filtered within the where clause in full.

This will allow me to add a third column (or calculation) that shows the customer's portion of the entire total for the date range.



  select a.allocated_account_name,

 date(a.usage_start_time) as usage_date,

 sum(cost) as uip_cost,

 sum(cost) over (

 PARTITION BY date(a.usage_start_time)

 ORDER BY sum(cost)

 ROWS BETWEEN UNBOUNDED PRECEDING AND UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING

 ) as total_daily

 from `all-billing-data.all_billing_data.allocated_gcp_billing_export` a

 LEFT JOIN UNNEST(a.labels) on key='exa_product'

 where value='uip'

 group by 1,2

 order by 1 asc





The resulting columns would have:

1. account name
2. Usage date
3. UIP Cost for account on usage date
4. Total UIP Cost for ALL accounts on usage date



Running into errors with my group bys that I could use some help with. Thanks Dion

Tickets_Subject: Waterfall visuals question
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Magdalena:

I was testing and also conferred with my colleagues, unfortunately the built-in waterfall visual does not have too much customization to remove the Total.   I was able to get it to the point that the Total bar does not come by using the white color for the Total, plus removing Gridlines and changing the label value to white.   This will not stop the "Total" text to show up on the x-axis, unless you turn off the x-axis labelling.  For the tooltip, there is no direct option to remove that as well, but you can use a workaround [1] to handle that.


Now, with the work around you did to create the Waterfall effect based on the Community code you found, again unfortunately since this is a nothing but a Bar chart.   I was only able to add the transparent by setting the Series color in "custom" to "Transparent.  But this does not stop the tool tip to come up.  You may want to implement the workaround [1].





[1] https://help.looker.com/hc/en-us/articles/4420202170387-How-to-disable-tooltip-in-chart-entirely-Community-

Asad Khan (asad@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Eastern Time (US & Canada)).

Tickets_Subject: Format Issue - Thousand Comma in a String
Ticket_Comment_Body:
On a email of 06.10.2022 from Richard Kuo, he already mentioned the formats issue.



Situation:

- In Snowflake, we have **ONE field** with numbers and their corresponding measure (e.g.:1.000 Kg, 1.000.000 €, 50 %, 1,65 %, 150.000 ). The field is a VARCHAR in the database.
- In Looker, the field is called as a dimension type: string. So, it should keep the format, and show the values exactly as it appears in Snowflake.
- But in the case of the number 150.000 of the example, Looker changes the dot for a comma.

Tickets_Subject: Detail of the Looker licenses and allocation across 2 x instances
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Theory on answers:

1. how are developer / admin licenses spread across the 2 x instances for feefoIBI and feefoPBL?
  1. Licenses are per instance so they will need to purchase additional licenses for additional users
  2. Licenses can be allocated to particular users if they assign specific IAM roles
  3. For Example, Looker `Platform Advanced (Powered by Looker) - Looker Hosted` is Looker Hosted includes one production Instance, 10 Standard User (Powered by Looker) - Looker Hosted End Users, 2 Developer User - Looker Hosted End Users, upgrades, up to 1,000 query-based API calls per month, along with 1,000 administrative API calls per month, and embedding. This should imply that the instance will have 2 Developer users that can be allocated. `LookerUserInternalAdmin` should imply 6 additional Admins can be added to a particular instance
2. is it even necessary to have admins on the PBL instance or is that purely for external viewers?
  1. Admins are necessary even for Power By Looker (PBL) instances. They control how external users will access the data. Security best practices found in [1]
3. Do developer / user licenses count towards `internalViewer`
  1. As per roles documentation [2], InternalViewer should count as a regular user/viewer. InternalAdmin would count towards developer.

Requested clarification from Looker Slack chat. Update customer not later than tomorrow, 01/04/2023 3:00 PM EST.

[1]: https://developers.looker.com/embed/advanced-embedding/security-best-practices
[2]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/admin-panel-users-roles#permissions_and_looker_licenses

Tickets_Subject: Detail of the Looker licenses and allocation across 2 x instances
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Jonny,

Greatly appreciate your patience.

Based on the information provided, you had purchased the following platform licenses:


    LookerPlatformHostedAdvancedLookerPlatformPBLAdvanced


The above provide 1 production instance with 10 Standard User &  2 Developer User (Looker Hosted End Users) [1] each. Developer users are categorized as Admins [2] so you should be able to allocate at least 2 Admins to each instance.

Regarding the 6 additional Admin/Developer slots, those should be for a particular instance because, as per [3], licenses should be unique to a Looker instance. It is possible the users were split among the instances, however, I believe they were assigned to `LookerPlatformHostedAdvanced `due to the naming convention omitting `Powered By Looker` within the description. To confirm, we recommend contacting the Field Sales Representative that helped with this transaction. They should have more visibility on which instances these users were assigned and may be able to further assist in re-distributing the users, if needed.

Lastly, even for PBL instances, admins are necessary to help secure data access. Instance Admins are required to review security best practices noted in [4] but we also recommend Admins create permission [5] & model [6] sets as they would greatly assist in managing data access levels for multiple user groups. If needed, a detailed explanation on permissions management can be found in [7].

I hope this clarifies everything. If you have any additional questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to ask.

[1]: https://cloud.google.com/terms/looker/legal/customers/licensing
[2]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/admin-panel-users-roles#permissions_and_looker_licenses
[3]: https://help.looker.com/hc/en-us/articles/4420181996179-Settings
[4]: https://developers.looker.com/embed/advanced-embedding/security-best-practices
[5]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/admin-panel-users-roles#permission_sets
[6]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/admin-panel-users-roles#model_sets
[7]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/access-control-and-permission-management

Sincerely,


Gurkomal

DoiT International [Eastern Time US & Canada]

Tickets_Subject: Issue with Community Vizualisation on Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
We have an issue while using a community vizualisation on Looker.



When embedding a looker studio report in a web page using an iframe, a warning panel displays when I put my cursor over the community vizualisation. (please find attach the vizualisation)

This problem was not here before the 28th of december 2022.



What you expected to happen:

No warning panel when hovering the community vizualization or at least a configuration in looker studio to deactivate the warning.



Steps to reproduce:

1. Create a looker studio report

2. Create a spreadsheet, fill values in the first lines of the first sheet of the spreadhsheet to represent a data source

3. Connect the looker studio report to the spreadsheet as a data source

4. Add a community vizualization in the looker studio report (e.g. CSV filter or sunburst chart)

5. Enable embedded report

6. Copy embed iframe code for embed report

7. On your local PC, create a simple html file, paste the iframe code in the body of the html

8. Open a web navigator and connect to google with the same google account that the one you created the looker studio report with

9. Open your html file in the web navigator

10. When you hover your mouse on the community vizualization, the following message appear in a panel :

"You are about to interact with a community visualization in this embedded report. Do not enter your password or other sensitive information in this area. Be careful interacting with third-party content."



Other information (documentation consulted, etc):

We have tried using the sandbox option with the iframe and disabling popups.

We have consulted forums, the CSV filter community vizualization documentation, looker studio developer documentation.

We created an issu on IssueTracker-Google : https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/264788280

We have found related issues : https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/260204224 https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/260299584

Best regards,

Axèle

Hello,

Google Cloud Support has added a comment to your Support Case 30273882 - Schedule reports from Looker instance failing:



Hi Dion,

Thanks so much for your reply.

Yes I agree this is challenging to catch since it is random and on Looker logs we just see a generic "Upload to SFTP host sftp://ftp.verabradley.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout" message. So, in this case the only step we can execute needs to be executed by customer and it is a packet capture:

1. Packet capture of when the connection is established.
2. They can use a tool like wireshark https://www.wireshark.org/ for this
3. Client MUST do this on SFTP server side, not from Looker side, as we want to see the messages from the SFTP server.
4. Once they have the previous steps they can filter the results by Looker IP requests and their server responses, and as well by traffic type (tcp and ssh).

We are trying to see if there is some kind of a miscommunication between servers, and this is the only way we can see it. And we would need to do this at least 2 times, one when connection is working as expected and another one and the most important, when the communication is failing. But as this is a random behavior customer need to be trying this until we have one failing with communication. As well, if they can keep trying with filezilla to have an incorrect communication log would be helpful, but pretty much packet capture is our best approach.

Regards,
José

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Here are my findings:
1. If the the data connections in the Looker model aren't set up correctly and that the data isn't pulling from the correct sources that could lead to the experienced behavior
2. If any filters are being applied to the data that may be preventing certain results from being returned.
3. If the measures in the visualization aren't being calculated correctly and that the correct fields aren't being used in the calculations, no records will be shown
4. If the correct dimension wasn't selected could be another issue

Tickets_Subject: SAML SSO - Avoid creating licenses unless approved by admin
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Arturo,

Please see this documentation to limit SSO/SAML user authentication. Here are the salient points:


The **Advanced Role Management** section contains these options:



**Prevent Individual SAML Users from Receiving Direct Roles**: Turning this option on prevents Looker admins from assigning Looker roles directly to SAML users. SAML users will receive roles only through their group memberships. If SAML users are allowed membership in native (not mirrored) Looker groups, they can still inherit their roles both from mirrored SAML groups and from native Looker groups. Any SAML users who were previously assigned roles directly will have those roles removed when they next log in.



If this option is off, Looker admins can assign Looker roles directly to SAML users as if they were configured natively in Looker.



**Prevent Direct Membership in non-SAML Groups**: Turning this option on prevents Looker admins from adding SAML users directly to native Looker groups. If mirrored SAML groups are allowed to be members of native Looker groups, SAML users may retain membership in any parent Looker groups. Any SAML users who were previously assigned to native Looker groups will be removed from those groups when they next log in.



If this option is off, Looker admins can add SAML users directly to native Looker groups.



**Prevent Role Inheritance from non-SAML Groups**: Turning this option on prevents members of mirrored SAML groups from inheriting roles from native Looker groups. Any SAML users who previously inherited roles from a parent Looker group will lose those roles when they next log in.



If this option is off, mirrored SAML groups or SAML users who are added as members of a native Looker group will inherit the roles assigned to the parent Looker group.



**Auth Requires Role**: If this option is on, SAML users are required to have a role assigned. Any SAML users who do not have a role assigned will not be able to log in to Looker at all.



If this option is off, SAML users can authenticate to Looker even if they have no role assigned. A user with no assigned role will not be able to see any data or take any action in Looker, but they will be able to log in to Looker.



I don't think it's possible to use more than one G Workspace on a single Looker instance but I think you circumvent this by using Groups to segment your JOKR and Soudak users explicitly.



Please let me know your thoughts.


Thank you.

/dion
Dion Edge
Senior Cloud Data Architect
dion@doit-intl.com

Tickets_Subject: Days Left in Quarter
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Thinking they can build separate measures for both of these and display in a stacked bar chart. Unfortunately I can't find how to do a stacked bar chart in Looker.

Using the code here as my basis[1].

Thought is to determine where you are at in the quarter and store that in a dimension. Then the next dimension will contain the sales target data.

You would then display these on a stacked bar chart.

Code:

    dimension_group: created_date { type: time timeframes: [#for our purposes we need doy, qoy, year raw, date, day_of_year, #1-366 integer quarter_of_year, #Q1-Q2-Q3-Q4 string for dayofquarterindex case statement year #integer, used to account for leap years in q1daycount] datatype: date sql: ${TABLE}.created_date ;; } dimension: q1daycount { #accounts for 91 days in Q1 during leap years type: number sql: CASE WHEN MOD(${created_date_year}, 4) = 0 THEN 91 ELSE 90 END;; } dimension: dayofquarterindex { #returns day of quarter index int 1-92 type: number sql: DATEDIFF('day',date_trunc('quarter',${created_raw}),${created_date}) + 1 ;; }


[1] https://community.looker.com/dashboards-looks-7/quarter-to-date-trending-by-week-index-chart-6386

Tickets_Subject: Days Left in Quarter
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Michelle‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Sayle, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you are trying to visualize days left in a quarter and your quarterly sales targets in the same report.

I was doing some tinkering to try and discover how to do this, which led me on a rabbit hole quest but I was able to make some progress on this.

I want to preface this with I think we should all hop on a call with our resident Looker expert, whom is unfortunately out sick today, later this week as I would love to hear his thoughts on this as well. If you could share your availability for later this week I can get something set up.

My thoughts on this are to create two dimensions that contain where you are in the current quarter timewise and another containing where you are in the quarter sales target-wise. Then plotting this in a "multivariate" chart such as a stacked bar chart, maybe a bar chart with a line on it, or maybe even a combination using both of these. I think this point is where we could definitely have a good discussion on a call to determine what would work best.

As for implementing this I was trying to get my head around how this would be done and found this forum post here[1] which I think does a phenomenal job of implementing this cleanly. Here is the code I was able to build from it[2] for doing the placement in quarter calculation using a created_date value from the data source. I also threw in a quarter calculator because it was bugging me seeing the start dates of the quarter in there. Note this is using the BQ SQL syntax in case you are using a different database.

Then for your sales target you would need to do a calculation of it for each day (I don't know what your data looks like so it probably wouldn't be useful to build some code for it that probably would just be thrown away) and it should be just displaying those two dimensions on the graph to make it work. That's the part I would love to discuss in the call.

If you could just share your availability and I will sync with some of our Looker SMEs so we put our heads together to find the best way to implement this.

[1] https://community.looker.com/dashboards-looks-7/quarter-to-date-trending-by-week-index-chart-6386

[2]

    dimension: days_into_quarter { # Returns difference between start of quarter and created_date type: number sql: date_diff(date_trunc(${created_raw}, QUARTER), ${created_date}, DAY) + 1 ;; }dimension: quarter { # Returns the n type: number sql: CASE WHEN date_trunc(${created_date}, QUARTER) = '2023-01-01' THEN 1 WHEN date_trunc(${created_date}, QUARTER) = '2023-04-01' THEN 2 WHEN date_trunc(${created_date}, QUARTER) = '2023-07-01' THEN 3 WHEN date_trunc(${created_date}, QUARTER) = '2023-01-01' THEN 4 END ;; }


Sincerely,

Sayle Matthews (sayle@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Central Time (US & Canada)).

Tickets_Subject: Looker bug support
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi DoIt!



I have a question around how we at Storytel should go about a support ticket we have filed to the Looker support.



In mid november we found that date formatting in many of our core dashboards were all of a sudden formatted very oddly. More specific, the dates had changed from being formatted as "2022-11-01" to "Sun Nov 20 00:00:00 2022" without us making any changes to the code. While this might not seem like a major problem, many of our Looker users reached out and complained about this new format was very hard to read and make sense of the data in. We investigated the problem and found that this odd formatting happens in specific cases, namely when we are making use of a "date granularity" dimension that refers to a parameter to toggle between weekly, monthly, daily granularity (see print attached). In addition to using this dimension, it is only when we use a pivot in a visualisation when this appears.



These very specific circumstances together with the fact that it showed up over night makes us believe this is a bug introduced by Looker. We have reached out to the Looker support, which haven't been able to provide us any solution other than turning on the legacy feature "Legacy Lookml Run time". The "Legacy Lookml Run time" is a Legacy feature that will be removed in 2 months from now. Since we have been in contact with Looker about this for soon to be 2 months without any progression and the date for removing this legacy feature is slowly approaching, I am now reaching out to you to hear what we can do in this case (and future similar cases) where we get no support or answer from Looker.



I attach some screen shots to display the problem. I fully understand if you cannot support in the technical solution, but hoping to get some advice how to tackle our support questions.



Best,

Moa

Tickets_Subject: Looker Studio Connector Requests Looker License
Ticket_Comment_Body:
> ...having only the Looker Studio license from the GSuite.

this is not true / possible:

**View and edit the data source configuration**

- You must be a Looker user with at least `explore` permissions to complete these steps

**View Looker data on a report**

- If you do not have a Looker account, the admin for the connected Looker instance must create one for you. You must have at least `access_data` and `clear_cache_refresh `permissions for the model on which the Explore is based to view data from Looker data sources.

+

The Looker connector is generally available for Looker instances on Looker 23.0 or later that are hosted by Looker in the Google Cloud. **The connector is not available for customer-hosted Looker instances or Looker instances that are not hosted in the Google Cloud. <<---!!!! **




also see this troubleshooting guideline: https://support.google.com/looker-studio/answer/12388266#troubleshooting&zippy=%2Cin-this-article

Tickets_Subject: Looker Studio Connector Requests Looker License
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Federico,

Here are the prerequisites to enable Looker Studio on your Looker instance:

**View and edit the data source configuration**

- You must be a Looker user with at least `explore` permissions to complete these steps

**View Looker data on a report**

- If you do not have a Looker account, the admin for the connected Looker instance must create one for you. You must have at least `access_data` and `clear_cache_refresh `permissions for the model on which the Explore is based to view data from Looker data sources.

**Before the connector can be used, the following prerequisites must be met:**


- The Looker connector must be enabled in Looker Studio.
- If your Looker instance has the **Enable Allowlist** toggle enabled, you will need to allowlist the IP addresses that are used by Looker Studio (contact Support for the full list).
- Your Looker instance's Explores must use a database dialects connection that is supported by Looker Studio.
- Once the connector is enabled, Looker Studio users with `access_data` and `clear_cache_refresh` Looker permissions can view Looker data in a Looker Studio report.

Please, let me know if you have any further questions.

Thank you.

/dion
Dion Edge
Senior Cloud Data Architect
dion@doit-intl.com

Tickets_Subject: Contingent Reports or better Alerts
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello DoiT team,



We are trying to find better ways to use Looker for alerting, e.g. when a certain metric is above/below some threshold.



We currently use the "Schedule delivery" feature (https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/scheduling-and-sending-dashboards) on a lot of our dashboards to send messages into Slack. However, these messages get sent out regardless of any metric/threshold. Is there a way to add a threshold to scheduled delivery so a dashboard only gets sent into Slack contingent on some condition?



Alternatively, we have looked at using Looker Alerts (https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/alerts-overview). However, the content of these alerts seems to be very limited. In the case of Slack alerts, we can't embed a png of the visualization nor a CSV of the data, and we can't even link back to the dashboard.



In either case (Schedule delivery or Alerts) we'd like to be able to customize the content of the Slack message. In order to make the messages as actionable as possible, the content of the message would ideally be dynamic based on the dashboard results.



Is there any way to accomplish some/all of these requirements with Looker? Happy to discuss live if that's easier.



Best,

Andrew

Ticket_Comment_Body:
As mentioned on Slack, here are two things I saw in your BQ setup that could be fixed to improve performance and possibly assist on some of these performance issues.

`campgladiator-production.relational_data.vw_subscriptions_data.Purchase_Date_CST` is used a LOT for dates in these queries and especially around intervals in the past. I would HIGHLY recommend recreating that table and partitioning on that field by day or month. This will give you a massive speed up in your queries.

In the same vein in `campgladiator-production.relational_data.vw_subscriptions_data` has two fields which has values checked on it a lot. The fields `Product` and `Status` are queried by the Looker user a lot. If you put a cluster on these two columns that would immensely speed up the queries on that table.

Sayle Matthews (sayle@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Central Time (US & Canada))

Tickets_Subject: Looker Studio Connector Requests Looker License
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hey Josh,
So I got to take a deep dive this morning into your data and ran a few of my "magic queries" on it which look at your query executions. I have attached the data I pulled from your environment for the longest running queries, with the query here[1]. Recommend loading this up in Sheets really fast to see what's going on.

You will notice at the start there are a few from this morning that took a really long time to run for some reason. I will cover those here later in this message as I think these were outliers, but as more data comes in there could be an issue later as data grows. Otherwise you will notice that practically all of your Looker queries (ones with looker-cg-779 in the user field) are sub-second or close to it.

As for the performance issues here I am passing this back to Dion as he back in the office for opening up a ticket with the Looker team. This appears to be something in Looker itself that's causing performance issues as the queries are running fast and processing minimal data (<100 MB which is like the size of an ant to a human in BQ terms).

As for the potential issues going forward I just grabbed that first slow query in there as a good example (job ID `job_dWwXL8-n0ac_BzQ-F5sJ67r6a8nG`) since it references a view a lot of the others do as well and ran this query to pull it's execution plan[2]. It's not easy to see in there but there is a column called `timeline.elapsed_ms` which is the time it took for each step to run. If you look at it the longest step is a "Join+" step which makes sense as joins are VERY slow in BQ so I started digging deeper into where a JOIN is happening.

I noticed it's traced back down to the `vw_subscriptions_data` view which has this join condition in it[3]. If you notice in there it's pulled id, name, and email out multiple times from the `public_trainers` table. Doing this same condition multiple times is definitely causing it to run MUCH slower than it should by doing multiple joins. This is also causing a condition called shuffling inside of the query execution which means that it is having to push data between compute nodes inside of BigQuery's core which is very slow, if you are familiar with operating systems this is very close to the same concept as virtual memory which means computations on disk versus memory slowdowns.

What I would recommend doing is to "pre-compute" this view instead of using it as a view meaning to build a physical table that defined as `CREATE TABLE vw_subscriptions_data AS <view definition query here>` instead. If it needs to be updated relatively often then I would recommend doing a rebuild on this on a schedule. The reasoning being is that when you query a view it runs the definition of it in the background so it's doing all of those joins every time it executes, if you only do that once when you build the query you are just doing reads when querying not joins.

I know this is a lot here, but if you would like me to do a BQ best practices session feel free to open up a ticket with us and just drop my name saying you would like this and I would be glad to host a working session to go over this.

With all of that said I am passing this back on to Dion so he can do a deep dive into the Looker part or raising a ticket with Google as needed because this is appearing to be a Looker issue.

Sayle

[1] https://github.com/doitintl/bigquery-optimization-queries/blob/main/information_schema/longest_running_queries.sql
[2]

    SELECT *FROM `region-us`.INFORMATION_SCHEMA.JOBS_BY_PROJECTWHERE job_id = 'job_dWwXL8-n0ac_BzQ-F5sJ67r6a8nG'

[3]

    FROM `campgladiator-production.relational_data.public_subscriptions` as subsLEFT JOIN (SELECT id, CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name) AS Name,email,phone,gender FROM `campgladiator-production.relational_data.public_users` ) as users on users.id = subs.user_idLEFT JOIN (SELECT id, CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name) AS Name,email FROM `campgladiator-production.relational_data.public_trainers` ) as SellT on SellT.id = subs.sales_repLEFT JOIN (SELECT id, CONCAT(first_name, ' ', last_name) AS Name,email FROM `campgladiator-production.relational_data.public_trainers` ) as ServT on ServT.id = subs.servicing_trainerLEFT JOIN `relational_data.vw_program_schedule_address` as psa on psa.id = subs.program_schedule_id

Tickets_Subject: Rolling Throughput Yield Calculation from a Periodic Snapshot table
Ticket_Comment_Body:
NOTE: I scheduled a meeting with Dion to discuss this tomorrow. Submitting the ticket so he has something to log the work against.



PROBLEM STATEMENT

Mfg team wantS to modify how we calculate Yields to be a Rolling Throughput Yield, where the pseudo-code for the calculation is:



LEAST(Line 2000 Yield %, Line 2008 Yield %)

x Line 2001 Yield %

x Line 2002 Yield %

x Line 2003 Yield %

x Line 2004 Yield %

x Line 2005 Yield %



Yield % is defined as (# of Good Parts) / (# of Good Parts + # of Bad Parts)



Data source is a periodic snapshot with all of the Lines basically UNION ALL (on top of each other).



Looker translates it into the SQL included in the attached file. SQL returns this error: Query execution failed: - SELECT list expression references mfg_cell_consolidated_hourly_snapshot.acl_line which is neither grouped nor aggregated at [4:19]



I need a better approach, ideally with the same dataset b/c I need to incorporate this into our existing OEE dashboard.

Tickets_Subject: Single filter controlling multiple dimensions
Ticket_Comment_Body:
- I did some research and discovered the following post https://community.looker.com/explores-36/date-range-filter-with-relative-dates-11507 about date range filter that has a relative type with **start** (1st date filter) and **end** (2nd date filter) points (_kind of similar to what my client is trying to accomplish_)
- It looks like a date filter with relative type according to https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/filter-expressions#relative_dates is the way to go

Tickets_Subject: Single filter controlling multiple dimensions
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Taek,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Steeve and I will be assisting you with setting up a single date filter on the dashboard to control two date filters simultaneously.

After conducting a thorough research, I think using Looker's Relative Dates [1] feature, will allow you to create queries with rolling date values relative to the current date. With a relative date filter, you can display the selected period and previous period on the same chart or visualization without the need for a separate "reporting date" field. This provides a more efficient and streamlined approach to comparing different time periods.

Here are the steps to implement a relative date filter in Looker to allow comparison of any selected period to the previous equivalent period, while still using a single date filter on the dashboard:

1. Open the dashboard that contains the period-on-period view in Looker.
2. Click on the date filter that you want to modify.
3. In the "Filter" section, change the filter type to "Relative".
4. Check the box "Allow Users to Override Relative Dates".
5. In the "Value Format" section, select "SQL".
6. In the "SQL" section, enter something like the following:
`BETWEEN dateadd({{view.period}}, -1, {{dashboard.datefilter_field}}) AND {{dashboard.datefilter_field}}`
_Please make sure to replace_ _"view.period" with the name of the period field in your view, and replace "dashboard.datefilter_field" with the name of the date field in your dashboard._
7. Save your changes.

Kindly let me know if that work for you.

[1]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/filter-expressions#relative_dates

Best,

Steeve
steeve@doit-intl.com
DoiT International [Eastern Time US & Canada].

Tickets_Subject: Single filter controlling multiple dimensions
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Dion,



I think I've solved the WTD filter starting from Sundays. Used a date_diff around week(weekday) to set the comparisons from Monday rather than EXTRACT(DAYOFWEEK()). This seems to be working!



    sql: 
          (DATE_DIFF(${completed_tz_raw},DATE_TRUNC(${completed_tz_raw}, WEEK(MONDAY)),DAY)+1 < DATE_DIFF(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), DATE_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), WEEK(MONDAY)), DAY)+1
              OR
            (DATE_DIFF(${completed_tz_raw}, DATE_TRUNC(${completed_tz_raw}, WEEK(MONDAY)),DAY)+1 = DATE_DIFF(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(),DATE_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), WEEK(MONDAY)), DAY)+1 AND
            EXTRACT(HOUR FROM ${completed_tz_raw}) < EXTRACT(HOUR FROM CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()))
              OR
          	(DATE_DIFF(${completed_tz_raw},DATE_TRUNC(${completed_tz_raw}, WEEK(MONDAY)),DAY)+1 = DATE_DIFF(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(),DATE_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), WEEK(MONDAY)),DAY)+1 AND
            EXTRACT(HOUR FROM ${completed_tz_raw}) <= EXTRACT(HOUR FROM CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()) AND
            EXTRACT(MINUTE FROM ${completed_tz_raw}) < EXTRACT(MINUTE FROM CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()))) ;;

Tickets_Subject: Syncing code across Looker instances.
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Jon, et al.

So, the pattern for User Attributes to parameterize database connections works for almost database except for GCP BigQuery because BQ uses a service account private key (the JSON file you attach to the connection). I did find this workaround that I am testing today but I thought I should share it now.


    There is a workaround using model sets, however. In this set up, we'll create multiple connections (1 per BQ project) and within out LookML project, 1 model per connection. We will then define our explore in a view file, or a .explore.lkml file (as these do not require a defined connection).Model file 1:include: "bq_base_explores.view.lkml"connection: "bq-project-1"Model file 2:include: "bq_base_explores.view.lkml"connection: "bq-project-2"View file/explore file (bq_base_explores.view.lkml) :explore: abcexplore: xyzWe will then define 2 model sets, one with permissions to model 1 and one for model 2, and assign these to users who would fall into our different UA groups. Our explores will be available to both sets of users, but will be queried against different connections depending on the user.


Please let me know your thoughts.

Thank you.

/dion
Dion Edge
Senior Cloud Data Architect

Tickets_Subject: Looker filter
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello! I have a question about some filter functionality in Looker. Let's say I have a table called fact_survey_response that contains records for feedback surveys that users complete and it has a grain of one row per user per survey response that a user submits. A single user can submit many responses.



A user belongs to an organization, and each organization can have a "trusted" relationship with X number of other organizations.



Assume we have:

- fact_survey_response - one row per user per survey response that a user submits, this has a score value of 0-10.
- dim_organization - one row per organization with org attributes
- bridge_organization_to_trusted_organization - one row per organization per organization they trust



I want to be able to show data from an explore based on fact_survey_response, filtered by the trusted organization, but **without increasing the grain of fact_survey_response when joining to the trusted organizations**. I'm imagining a way to select a value in a Looker filter and it creates a query like this:

    SELECT <useful columns>
    FROM fact_survey_response
    WHERE survey_organization_id IN
        (SELECT trusted_organization_id FROM bridge_organization_to_trusted_organization WHERE trusted_by_organization_id IN(<list of filter input values>))

Is this possible with Looker filters? It seems like there are ways to make the filters dynamic but I can't quite figure this one out.



Here's a visual of the relationship between these entities, if that helps! Thanks!
 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/frWIJl7x6CM322X7XQ7EOkPtO/?name=hxaxcsgb.png)

Tickets_Subject: Looker Slack Connection Issues
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Since 3/20/23 we've been having issues with our Looker Slack connection.



1. Using the scheduler within Looker to send a dashboard to Slack, we can no longer send to a user. Sending to a channel still works.
2. Using a custom script that updates schedules in Looker
3. When specifying a destination of a Slack channel, it no longer works to enter the channel as say #data-mgtmt-reports, but have to use the channel ID eg C03Q654PRB6
4. When specifying a destination of a Slack user, it no longer works at all. It was working by entering the user as say @bwickersheim but neither this or the user ID works now.



These are new issues. Everything had been working for several months.



Item 1 has nothing to do with our custom system, so the issue there is within the Looker Slack connection.



fyi, a couple of snippets from the custom python script:



    from looker_sdk import models40
    sdk = looker_sdk.init40()



    if schedule['destination'] == 'Slack Channel':
        destination_type = 'looker-integration://1::slack'
        parameters = '{"channelType":"channels","channel":"' + schedule['deliver_to'] + '","initial_comment":"' \
                     + schedule['title'] + '","filename":"' + schedule['title'] + '"}'

    if schedule['destination'] == 'Slack User':
        destination_type = 'looker-integration://1::slack'
        parameters = '{"channelType":"users","channel":"' + schedule['deliver_to'] + '","initial_comment":"' \
                     + schedule['title'] + '","filename":"' + schedule['title'] + '"}'

    destinations.append(
        models40.ScheduledPlanDestination(
            format=schedule['format_code'],
            type=destination_type,
            address=address,
            parameters=parameters,
            apply_formatting=True,
            apply_vis=True
        )
    )



Thanks,

Hello Dion,

Case Subject: Schedule reports from Looker instance failing

Case Comment :

José, sorry for very late summary but I think we should review this together and then set up a meeting with the customer. Please, let me know what you think. /dion

###############################################

Problem: Some scheduled Looks, but not all, are being killed by the SFTP server with a Looker generated error (paraphrased) remote host killed connection due to timeout.



Database: PostgreSQL 9.6 (default timeout is 30s but if the db is killing the query, I think we would get a SQL error in Looker, which we are not. I think the SFTP server is killing the query but I could be wrong (if the SFTP timeout is NULL, default is also 30s).

Investigation: We see the same timeout errors in the looker instance admin/scheduled_jobs and confirmed:



Same error

Multiple users

Different frequencies

40s timeouts



So, we picked one Look that was failing and observed:



No results returned

No database or LookML errors

No LookML errors in the model or view files

No unusual or complex LookML (weird syntax, extends, etc)

We turned on debug logging last evening so I am trying to focus on a recent event. Based on start and end times in this event, I have attached the syslog and auth.log. The logs include customer names etc. which should be covered under our NDA but please do not share with external parties.

```List of errors:

1. User Chethan Sindhie is not enabled. Contact your Looker administrator to re-assign this scheduled report to an enabled user.

2. Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp-prod.shopwithgolf.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout Job ID

1221817

3. Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed due to error: NoMethodError. message: undefined method `write' for nil:NilClass Job ID

1221731

4. Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed due to error: NoMethodError. message: undefined method `write' for nil:NilClass Job ID

1221630

5. Upload to SFTP host sftp://ftp.verabradley.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout Job ID

1221522

6. Upload to SFTP host sftp://ftp.verabradley.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout Job ID

1221523

7. Authentication to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user beautycounter_returns@sftp.narvar.com. Job ID

1221412

8. Upload to SFTP host sftp://216.107.192.79:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout Job ID

1221414

9. Authentication to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user parkerny_returns_reports@sftp.narvar.com. Job ID

1221240

10. Authentication to SFTP host sftp://test-sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user test_sftp@test-sftp.narvar.com. Job ID

1221188

11. Authentication to SFTP host sftp://test-sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user test_sftp@test-sftp.narvar.com. Job ID

1221185

12. Authentication to SFTP host sftp://test-sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user test_sftp@test-sftp.narvar.com. Job ID

1221183

13. Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp-prod.shopwithgolf.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout Job ID

1220920

Above is the list for failed jobs regarding SFTP, except for no. 1 which is not related at all but I do see a big number of failed jobs because of this issue "User 'SEVERAL USERS' is not enabled. Contact your Looker administrator to re-assign this scheduled report to an enabled user." So it will be good for Narvar to check those users and enable them or not, depending on their needs. Now, regarding the SFTP, I do see more success SFTP jobs than failed, I know this is not a sustained issue but the second common issue I see is this "Authentication to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed for user: Authentication failed for user 'SEVERAL USERS'" this is an issue with credentials that Narvar needs to solve on their end if it's the case or it may be that users are not properly entering the credentials for your SFTP.

Then, I do see some errors with:

"Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp-prod.shopwithgolf.com:22 failed due to error: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout. message: Net::SSH::ConnectionTimeout"

"Upload to SFTP host sftp://sftp.narvar.com:22 failed due to error: NoMethodError. message: undefined method `write' for nil:NilClass"

I'll investigate those ones and let you know my findings ASAP. But please, could you let me know how many times they do see failed sftp deliveries and when they see them do they go to https://narvar.looker.com/admin/scheduled_jobs page and check the reason of why it failed? ```

Tickets_Subject: Question on Users w/ both Email and Google Authentication
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello,

We're doing some user clean-up and have a question about users with both email and google authentication set up.



Reading through Looker documentation, it appears as if users with only google authentication don't automatically have their Looker accounts disabled when they leave our org, but we aren't concerned about their continued access since once their google authentication is revoked, they shouldn't be able to log into Looker.



What we aren't sure about is some of our early users who were first set up with email authentication and now also have google authentication. Once they leave the org and their google authentication is revoked, will their access via email authentication still allow them access to Looker? If so, how do we remove their email authentication access?
 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/0ioTJK9aXUKNlM85Gpjz3G97A/?name=qofwqsxw.png)


Also, we appear to have a Catherine Huang (cathuang@looker.com) from Looker as a User with an enabled account although she has never logged in. Is this normal or can we disable this account?
 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/0fYF2tTQlfnbEMFP7ZRbmbZIr/?name=qowycqhl.png)


Thanks, Jill

Thanks so much for responding. I'm not sure you could see the screenshot I included in the ticket, but here's another with an example. In this screenshot, Jad and me have both Email and Google authentication accounts while Jennifer is only Google. There aren't two distinct accounts with each type of authentication set up.

Tickets_Subject: Looker dashboard dynamic alert schedule
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Parham,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Derrick, and I am helping Andrea with this request.

I understand that you are looking for a way to dynamically send Looker Studio dashboard to individual email users.

There are currently two Looker Studio versions:

- **Looker Studio** - it used to be known as Data Studio, which is a free product without support from Google. Thus we at Doit will only provide **best-effort level support**.
- **Looker Studio Pro** - it is a new product that was launched last December. It adds more features to the free version, enhanced enterprise capabilities, and technical support.

For more details on the Pro version, you can check these links [1] [2] [3].

To start my investigation, I have a few questions:


- Could you clarify which Looker Studio version you use in your company?
- Where do you get the anomalies data, and where do they get stored? (BigQuery?)

Thanks, and I look forward to your reply.

[1] https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/data-analytics/an-introduction-to-looker-studio-pro/
[2] https://support.google.com/looker-studio/thread/184135643/announcing-looker-studio-and-looker-studio-pro?hl=en
[3] https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/data-analytics/an-introduction-to-looker-studio-pro


Sincerely,

Sincerely,

Derrick Qin (derrick@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International Australia(Melbourne)

Tickets_Subject: Dynamically limiting data on a looker dashboard
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello,

I'm trying to limit the data to a particular customer of ours for a dashboard I'm integrating into our web app via an iFrame.

I have no problem integrating the dashboard into the iFrame and displaying that. The user has full control of the filters on the dashboard, and everything is great. Except, one of the filters is the name of the customer and I only want them to be able to see data for their customer.

I was hoping there was a way to define in looker that this dashboard needs a query parameter and the value of that parameter will be used to limit the data being displayed. Is that possible? If not what is the best solution for us to provide this functionality?

Tickets_Subject: Limiting Cross Filtering to Specific Tiles
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi DoIT,



I'm trying to tackle something that is not natively available on Looker which is the limiting of cross filtering to certain tiles.



To be more specific, my problem is as follows.



I currently have a dashboard containing some data relating to transactions.



The data is broken down into market categories of which there a dozen, each containing ~1-40 merchant categories.



For both of these entities I have things like average dollar spend and number of transactions which I would like to be able to show specifically for each merchant category or market segment that is selected on screen via the cross filtering ability.



I have screenshots below to demonstrate my current output.



 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/KVy5rEuzldpu8eHm45z6XHeKy/?name=oskyurbd.png)




So in the first image I have the market segment of retail selected in top left tile which cross filters to the specific merchant categories in the bottom left tile.



Furthermore it filters both the right tiles to show the transactions and average spend values for this market segment.



 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/1x0oTJjmPXkKPPIFly7D3Kl6S/?name=lhkfiyea.png)


Now in this second image I have the merchant category selected from the bottom left tile of discount stores.



What this does is filter both the right tiles which is my problem.



My intended functionality is for the top right tile to ignore this cross filter as it references the market segment and not the merchant category (which the bottom right tile is for).



Ideally I would like the cross filtering of the market segment to affect the bottom left and top right tile while the cross filtering of the merchant category only affect the bottom right tile.



Hence my issue is that the cross filtering is universal and not specific for each tile which is something I would like to try achieve.



What i have tried so far is playing around with a few case statements as filters but i have no been able to progress much.



I have researched online and found a single comment outlining that they used filters to achieve this.



Here is the link with the last comment being the one i am talking about -



https://community.looker.com/dashboards-looks-7/cross-filtering-some-tiles-not-all-of-them-27772



Any help would be appreciated regarding this!



Paiwand

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Yeah it's definitely got my gears spinning and I'm sure there is some way around it either through LookML logic via a view or hopefully just some custom expressions as filters for the tiles.



I was thinking something along the lines of checking if there is a filter selected using the matches_filter function on the market segment or merchant category dimensions and building some conditional output on that.



However, I quickly found that the matches_filter function is limited to having a string input for its second argument alongside the fact that I don't think something that is not filtered on can have its filter value checked.



Beyond what I explained previously - there are probably a few edge cases where the dash will be break too so I'm quite stumped with what a robust solution can be.



Looking forward to what you can put together!



Paiwand

Tickets_Subject: Looker Studio returning data for wrong date
Ticket_Comment_Body:
We have a data source set up in Looker Studio via BiqQuery (named diDNALoads).



We noticed that Looker Studio is returning data that is 1 day off from the date field set in the BQ Data Source. For example, if we set the date to return as 5/4/23, it will return the data from 5/3/23. (See attached screenshot)



The BQ data source tables are partitioned by date (see attached screenshot). It looks like Looker Studio is using the partition date from BigQuery tables rather than the date field column from the data source. (attached screenshot of available fields from the data source).



We would appreciate any insight you all may have into this issue.

Tickets_Subject: schedule plan timezone
Ticket_Comment_Body:
We have an embed user on our instance who have scheduled plans for 5+ Looks.



The scheduled destination is S3 bucket, from sudoing the user, we see that the time of schedule is set to 6am on all of them (on this schedule interface there's no option to choose timezone). From the actually schedule job history, we see that these schedules are sent some at 6am UTC, some at 1pm UTC. The ones sent at 1pm UTC has US/Los Angeles as the timezone in the system data.



We're not sure why this is the case and where we can control / update the timezone.

Tickets_Subject: schedule plan timezone
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Aaron‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Renato, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you have scheduled exports for 5+ Looks and some of them showing different delivery hours even though all of them are point to 6:00 am.

According to Looker documentation [1]:


> _The **Application Time Zone** is the default time zone for_ _content deliveries__. The time zone used for content deliveries does not affect time-based data returned by a query; it affects only the time a data delivery is sent._
>
>
>
> _If you enable the_ _**User Specific Time Zones**_ _option, the **Application Time Zone** is the default time zone for users that do not have a time zone value set for their accounts._


Can you check the Application time zone set for this user and if the User Specific Time zone is enabled?

[1] https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/using-time-zone-settings#application_time_zone


Sincerely,

Renato Shimabukuro (renato@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Central Time (US & Canada))

User Specific Timezone is disabled. Application Time Zone is UTC set at Looker Admin - Settings, which I assume applies to all users.



Best,

Aaron

Tickets_Subject: Re: Looker Reports using GDrive Action Fail to Complete Regularly
Ticket_Comment_Body:
![Google Cloud](https://vector.my.salesforce.com/servlet/servlet.ImageServer?id=015f4000002r9PP&oid=00Df40000023Flu)



Hello Ken,

 I have gone through the previous executions (up to a month) of each schedule that failed to deliver on time and here are my observations:

- The deliveries complete successfully after the time stated in the Schedule History page.
- On the Action Hub server I can see one of multiple tries for several of the schedules - the complete action from the AH server takes no longer than 1 minute in most schedules and we receive no errors.
- Since all scheduling is happening on a single user I theorized that there could be throttling due to us hitting the Per user query limit. I quickly refuted this idea because the schedules seem to be triggering and completing within 2 minutes on both Looker and Action Hub.
 This observations make me think that we may be hitting a Drive/Workspace issue with either throttling or the streaming of results - there's no indication on the Looker or AH side that could shed some light as to why deliveries take over 6 hours to show up on drive.

 For next steps I would like to test the Drive delivery to a work folder I own to be able to track the timing of the delivery and replicate the issue on command. Please let me know if you'd approve of this as a further Action Hub troubleshooting step or if you have any questions.

    Alejandro S, TSE
    Looker - Google Cloud Support

Tickets_Subject: Re: Looker Reports using GDrive Action Fail to Complete Regularly
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Matthew,

Our Google support engineer and the case manager was hoping to get approval to perform the additional testing described in their last update to this support case. Is this something you would be willing to approve for them to continue their troubleshooting on this very elusive problem? Providing an approval either in response to this request on the Google support case (made on Tuesday of this week) or here, I can then forward that approval over to their team. We appreciate your patience with this issue as it gets worked.



> I have gone through the previous executions (up to a month) of each schedule that failed to deliver on time and here are my observations:
>
>
>
> - The deliveries complete successfully after the time stated in the Schedule History page.
> - On the Action Hub server I can see one of multiple tries for several of the schedules - the complete action from the AH server takes no longer than 1 minute in most schedules and we receive no errors.
> - Since all scheduling is happening on a single user I theorized that there could be throttling due to us hitting the Per user query limit. I quickly refuted this idea because the schedules seem to be triggering and completing within 2 minutes on both Looker and Action Hub.
>
> This observations make me think that we may be hitting a Drive/Workspace issue with either throttling or the streaming of results - there's no indication on the Looker or AH side that could shed some light as to why deliveries take over 6 hours to show up on drive.
>
>
>
> **For next steps I would like to test the Drive delivery to a work folder I own to be able to track the timing of the delivery and replicate the issue on command. Please let me know if you'd approve of this as a further Action Hub troubleshooting step or if you have any questions.**

Ken Barker (ken@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International

Tickets_Subject: Performance issues with System Activity explores
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hey Dion,

I think this might be due to the concurrent query limit for system activity queries. Without System Activity Elite, they will be limited to 1 query at a time. Besides that, I think usually issues with system activity explores are due to the size of the underlying database tables. Running a query in each explore, especially the history table, with a simple count could give us an idea here. If that is the issue, we would also have to reach out to GCP support to see if they can trim the tables, due to the performance issues that they are causing. This would mean, that the data wouldn't be available for the customer to analyse anymore.

https://www.googlecloudcommunity.com/gc/Technical-Tips-Tricks/Why-are-my-System-Activity-queries-being-queued/ta-p/585263

https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/usage-reports-with-system-activity-explores

Tickets_Subject: Analytics, BQ lens, optimization of BQ search
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Gisele‍,

I hope this message finds you well.

It seems you were unable to meet for the call today but I would like to still offer some information that can help optimize your BigQuery environment.

As a general recommendation, it's strongly advised to utilize partitioned tables [1] in order to significantly enhance query performance. Partitioning offers several benefits, including reduced bytes scanned by queries, resulting in lower costs for those on on-demand pricing. For the BigQuery Editions (slot-hour) pricing model, partitioning decreases the amount of data that needs to be processed, leading to a reduction in slot utilization.

Once you've implemented partitioned tables, the next step is to potentially implement clustered columns [2]. Clustering enables BigQuery to optimize query performance by organizing your data into blocks, which facilitates a process known as block pruning (removal of un-related data). Automatic re-clustering [3] ensures that newly added data is appropriately grouped with the corresponding storage blocks. As a result, BigQuery can efficiently sort and group data, leading to faster and more cost-effective query execution. Please note, block pruning is as best effort and may not guarantee cost reductions but is still generally recommended by the BigQuery product team.

For enhanced performance of reports and dashboards, we recommend considering BigQuery BI Engine [4] for fast, in-memory data processing. Please be aware that BI Engine requires the allocation of reservations and may not be suitable for all scenarios. It's essential to compare the increased costs against the performance gains derived from using this feature.

Lastly, you may always reschedule another meeting via [5] and we can further discuss the above via Google Meets.

[1]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/partitioned-tables
[2]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/clustered-tables
[3]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/clustered-tables#automatic_reclustering
[4]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/bi-engine-intro
[5]: https://go.doit.com/gurkomal-15min-discovery

Sincerely,

Gurkomal
gurkomal@doit-intl.com
DoiT International [Eastern Time US & Canada]

Tickets_Subject: Performance issues with System Activity explores
Ticket_Comment_Body:
![Google Cloud](https://vector.my.salesforce.com/servlet/servlet.ImageServer?id=015f4000002r9PP&oid=00Df40000023Flu)



Hello Dion,
 The system__activity model is available for all instances, but by default it is based directly on your Looker instance's internal MySQL database, the same database that is used for internal operations on your instance. For example, whenever you run a query on your instance, Looker will run an INSERT statement to add a row to the history table in your internal MySQL database with the details of that query. The problem with this setup is that MySQL is a transactional database, which means while it is very optimized for performing the operations that make your instance run, it is not well-optimized to run analytical SELECT queries. For instances with a significant level of activity, some of the tables can become large enough that SELECT statements on those tables run very slowly.

 When Elite System Activity is enabled, we provision a BigQuery replica of your internal MySQL database to use for System Activity. BigQuery is better optimized to run these kinds of queries than MySQL, so the System Activity queries run against the BigQuery replica, while your instance's operations continue to be performed using the original MySQL database.

 (Since the i__looker model is deprecated in favor of the system__activity model, i__looker continues to run against the MySQL database even after ESA is enabled.
 You can change the model for your content based on i__looker over to system__activity using the methods in this help center article: https://help.looker.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001288308-Changing-the-Model-or-Explore-of-a-Look)
 You can read more about challenges with transactional databases and the reasons to use a replica for analytics here: https://cloud.google.com/learn/what-are-transactional-databases

 I am not seeing any issues with the instance resource usage or any limitation being hit. Upgrading to the Elite System Activity will help resolve the performance issue with System Activity Explorers.

 Hope this is helpful. Let me know if there is anything else I can help with.

Kosalan
 Google Cloud Support

Tickets_Subject: Analytics, BQ lens, optimization of BQ search
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Gisele‍,

Greatly appreciate joining the meeting today. As discussed, I will reach out to a Looker specialist to further assist you in generating your reports. Please expect a response shortly.

In addition, please find below a summary of what we had discussed:

- For automating report generation, key products/services to consider would be BigQuery Scheduled queries [1], Cloud Composer [2] and Cloud Functions [3].
- Reports will be viewed in Looker Studio
- Prefer an out of the box solution

Cloud Composer would provide the most flexibility & features; however, this also causes it to be the most costly of the above options. As a sample, the following article [4] provides a brief overview of how another user leverages Cloud Composer/Apache Airflow to automate generating reports.

Cloud Functions can also provide similar features but would be limited when tasks need to harmonize with each other to form an orchestrated workflow. As a sample, the following article [5] provides an overview of automated reporting via Cloud Functions/Cloud Scheduler. The end results are viewed within Looker Studio (Formerly Data Studio).

[1]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/scheduling-queries
[2]: https://cloud.google.com/composer?hl=en
[3]: https://cloud.google.com/functions
[4]: https://medium.com/pasarpolis-product-tech/automated-reporting-system-using-airflow-a62f2ce12e80
[5]: https://towardsdatascience.com/creation-of-an-etl-in-google-cloud-platform-for-automated-reporting-8a0309ee8a78

Sincerely,

Gurkomal
gurkomal@doit-intl.com
DoiT International [Eastern Time US & Canada]

Tickets_Subject: Speed up Looker instance
Ticket_Comment_Body:
![Google Cloud](https://vector.my.salesforce.com/servlet/servlet.ImageServer?id=015f4000002r9PP&oid=00Df40000023Flu)



Hello Dion,
 Hope you are doing well!

 For _https://taboola.cloud.looker.com _we have the next performance charts:

 ![cpumemorytab](cid:1bfd2e0f-27ba-47ab-bfee-a5c3dd942d9b@Image_0_ "cpumemorytab")

As we can notice, the instance seems to be really helpful on the infra part. We are not hitting any limit.
 So I am sure that the problem with the "long running queries" is with the DB you are using and how it manages the load of queries.
 Could you please verify and confirm the next with me?:
 - A significant number Scheduled Tasks being triggered at the same time with gaps with less than 1 min. (Admin -> Schedule Plan and/or Schedule History)
 - Datagroups also being triggered at the same time as the scheduled tasks.
 - Heavy Dashboards trying to be rendered (with more than 25 tiles).

 Why the last?, because if the DB is busy trying to complete queries at the same time it can overwhelm it, so in case this is the issue, we will have to redesing the scheduled time of these tasks. Furthermore, if we are trying to render Dashboards with more than 25 tiles I will recommend to split it in two dashboards since it is not recommended to have Dashboards with more than 25 tiles.
 I can also suggest  checking  on _Admin -> System Activity -> Performance Recommendations _, this will give us some recommendations for our Looks/Explores/Dashboards that we can implement.

 ![dbp](cid:bb1ac63a-1cc2-49d2-83ea-0ed8e0e2c456@Image_1_ "dbp")

 ![dbp2](cid:dc795f7e-d792-4049-9b0a-dc4a703eed27@Image_2_ "dbp2")

 The last two images display the performance of your DB (the one that runs your queries), and as we can notice we have some little peaks, but I can consider that at the moment it is still not a big issue. So I will strongly recommend just to follow the performance recommendations on the Admin Panel that was explained above, and also if needed, the next doc about "Optimize Looker Performance"(https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/best-practices/how-to-optimize-looker-server-performance).

 Kind Regards.
 Mauro Alejandro
 Looker Support

Tickets_Subject: Changes from other development branches getting merged at times.
Tickets_Rating_Comment: Professional support, and seems to have troubleshooted the issue so all good
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Amaury‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Cecilia, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that when pulling remote changes on a branch (not main), changes from other branches are also being pulled, which is causing confusion and requiring revert commits.

The master branch seems to be regenerated from time to time, even though the main branch is 'main'. Let's address these issues one by one:


- **Pulling Remote Changes:** In Git, when you pull remote changes, it fetches the changes from the remote repository and merges them into your current branch. If you're seeing changes from other branches, it's possible that those changes were merged into the branch you're pulling from. It's also possible that the branches were not properly isolated, causing changes to bleed over from one branch to another. To troubleshoot this issue, you could check the commit history of the branches involved to see if there were any unexpected merges. You could also review the branch management practices to ensure that changes are properly isolated to their respective branches.


- **Regeneration of Master Branch:** By default, Git uses 'master' as the name of the main branch. However, it's possible to change the name of the main branch, as you've done in your case. If the master branch is being regenerated, it could be due to a script or process that's not aware of the name change and is still referring to 'master'. To troubleshoot this issue, you could review any scripts or processes that interact with your Git repository to see if they're still referring to 'master'. You could also check the settings in your Git client or on your Git hosting service to ensure that 'main' is set as the default branch.

Could you try the suggestions above and let me know the results, please?

Sincerely,

Cecilia Arenas (cecilia.arenas@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Paris)

Tickets_Subject: Calls for API are failing
Ticket_Comment_Body:
I went on a call with the customer and reviewed the behavior, as well as, discussed the issue with them and a TSE from Google. They rolled the instance back to version 23.8 but the issue persisted.

I then went over the shared code and error message and found that they were using a query_id to call the GET query_tasks endpoint. As per the documentation, the endpoint requires a query_task_id, not a query_id.

Afterwards I used the provided query_id in the POST query_tasks endpoint which generated a query_task_id.
When I used that query_task_id, the response body was returned with the status 200.

The assumption therefore was that somewhere in their script they are extracting and inserting the query_id instead of the query_task_id. The customer has started to go over their code, and the code that has been reviewed so far worked as expected in a local environment and also returned the query_task_id.

They are looking further into it, as their catalog application, which is utilizing the GET query_tasks endpoint, was moved to Kubernetes on Wednesday, it seems likely that it is related to that move and could potentially be a permissions issue.
