Tickets_Subject: Looker license in airgapped setup
Ticket_Comment_Body:
This was the response from Looker:


    Here's the documentation on renewing an offline Looker license. I've also made the request to sales ops to open a ticket to request to extend the 90 day offline license renewal time.By default offline licenses expire in 90 days. The usual process to renew them is mostly manual and relies on the Offline License Renewal Portal.The customer must provide a member of the Support team with their License Key and looker.data file, which can be retrieved in a couple ways.The usual method is to use the "Renew" button on the Admin > General Settings page in the Looker UI. This will "download" the file, essentially just copying it to the downloads folder and renaming it license_data.If the license has already expired and the customer can no longer access their instance, they will need to manually retrieve the looker.data file from the Looker directory on their instance.Support will then input the License Key and data file into the Offline License Renewal Portal. This will download a new offline license file, which is then handed over to the customer.Note: It can take up to a minute for the renewal to complete. After it is successful, the link provided is valid for 24 hours and can be used to download the license file multiple times within the window.The customer installs the new license in one of two ways.The usual way is to upload the file using the UI on the General Settings page.Just like before it can also be done manually. The customer will need to rename the file to looker.license, place it in the same directory as their looker.jar file, and ensure it's owned and readable by the same user running the looker application.Zack SimkoverData Analytics Sales858-736-5385


I'll keep this ticket open to track the offline discussion.

Tickets_Subject: Looker model development using Native Derived Tables and "bind_all_filters"
Tickets_Rating_Comment: Dion was very engaging and competent. We explore a very difficult edge case and we solved it together with Jonathan. Thank you for all the help.
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Dear doiT support team,



I am try to implement a fairly complex model in Looker ML. I am try to use "bind_all_filters" with native derived table. I have tried to follow the docs [1] but with no luck. I have found a work around at the moment but I will much more prefer use the "bind_all_filters" and Native Derivate Table.



I am going to explain what I am try to do using a SQL query.



    WITH
      density_reference AS (
      WITH
        density_reference_base AS (
        SELECT
          density_base.polygon_id AS polygon_id,
          density_base.purchasing_power_quantile AS purchasing_power_quantile,
          density_base.h3_key AS h3_key,
          COALESCE(SUM(density_base.devices ), 0) AS sum_devices,
          COALESCE(SUM(density_base.events ), 0) AS sum_events
        FROM
          `huq-annapurna.huq__test_client.density_output` AS density_base
          -- I want the same filter here and in the outer query --
        GROUP BY
          1,
          2,
          3
      )
      SELECT
        MIN(density_reference_base.sum_devices ) AS min_devices,
        MAX(density_reference_base.sum_devices ) AS max_devices,
        MIN(density_reference_base.sum_events ) AS min_events,
        MAX(density_reference_base.sum_events ) AS max_events
      FROM
        density_reference_base
      -- No filter here --
    )
    SELECT
      density.polygon_id AS density_polygon_id,
      density.centre_name AS density_centre_name,
      density.purchasing_power_quantile AS density_purchasing_power_quantile,
      density.h3_key AS density_h3_key,
      SAFE_DIVIDE(SUM(density.devices), ( ANY_VALUE(density_reference.max_devices) )) AS density_devices_normalized_over_max
    FROM
      `huq-annapurna.huq__test_client.density_output` AS density
    CROSS JOIN
      density_reference
    -- I want the same filter here and in the very inner query --
    GROUP BY
      1,
      2,
      3,
      4



This is the result I want. Of course the SQL can be different as long as the logic is the same.



I have try to use bind filter creating multiple explores but I was not able to make it work. It would be nice to implement it with NDT and "bind_all_filters" at the moment I use a custom SQL derived table with filters injected via liquid but this creates friction in downstream development.



Thank you



Best



- [1] https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/reference/param-view-explore-source

Speed up Looker instance
Ticket_Comment_Body:
https://taboola.cloud.looker.com/explore/skimlinks/warehouse?qid=DKZx8uWjhWZcaakQgvVBea&toggle=vis

WITH halfhourly_link_report AS (




      -- Using daily table as filtering and date fields are less than one month
      -- Date filter: '7 days ago for 7 days'
      SELECT * FROM
      `skim-insights.wh.daily_agg_link_report`

    )
SELECT
    halfhourly_link_report.normalized_page_url  AS halfhourly_link_report_normalized_page_url,
    publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_domain_name  AS publisher_domain_metadata_publisher_domain_name,
    publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_name  AS publisher_domain_metadata_publisher_name,
    COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_clicks,
    SAFE_DIVIDE(COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.sales ), 0), COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0)) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_conversion_rate,
    COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.order_amount_gbp ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_order_amount_gbp,
    COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.sales ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_sales,
    SAFE_DIVIDE(COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.total_combined_commission_amount_gbp ), 0), COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0)) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_total_epc_gbp
FROM halfhourly_link_report
LEFT JOIN `skim-insights.mugic.publisher_domain_metadata`
     AS publisher_domain_metadata ON halfhourly_link_report.publisher_domain_id = publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_domain_id
WHERE ((
  ((( halfhourly_link_report.date_ts ) >= ((TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), DAY), INTERVAL -7 DAY))) AND ( halfhourly_link_report.date_ts ) < ((TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), DAY), INTERVAL -7 DAY), INTERVAL 7 DAY)))))


  ))
GROUP BY
    1,
    2,
    3
ORDER BY
    4 DESC
LIMIT 5000

Hello Dion,

Your Case 45529734 for Google Cloud Platform has been updated.

Case Subject: Customer requests increase in Looker instance size

Case Comment :

Hi Mauro Alejandro!

PROBLEM: Looker looks and explores are experiencing significant rendering latency.

I met with several of the customer's engineering team including the Looker administrator. By process of elimination we eliminated the following potential causes of the appreciable latency in Looker's rendering:

1. Instance resources have significant headroom.

2. The query we used for our analysis performed nominally the same in Looker SQL Runner and the BigQuery Console.

- https://taboola.cloud.looker.com/explore/skimlinks/warehouse?qid=DKZx8uWjhWZcaakQgvVBea&toggle=vis

```WITH halfhourly_link_report AS (

-- Using daily table as filtering and date fields are less than one month

-- Date filter: '7 days ago for 7 days'

SELECT * FROM

`skim-insights.wh.daily_agg_link_report`

)

SELECT

halfhourly_link_report.normalized_page_url AS halfhourly_link_report_normalized_page_url,

publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_domain_name AS publisher_domain_metadata_publisher_domain_name,

publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_name AS publisher_domain_metadata_publisher_name,

COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_clicks,

SAFE_DIVIDE(COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.sales ), 0), COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0)) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_conversion_rate,

COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.order_amount_gbp ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_order_amount_gbp,

COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.sales ), 0) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_sales,

SAFE_DIVIDE(COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.total_combined_commission_amount_gbp ), 0), COALESCE(SUM(halfhourly_link_report.clicks ), 0)) AS halfhourly_link_report_m_total_epc_gbp

FROM halfhourly_link_report

LEFT JOIN `skim-insights.mugic.publisher_domain_metadata`

AS publisher_domain_metadata ON halfhourly_link_report.publisher_domain_id = publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_domain_id

WHERE ((

((( halfhourly_link_report.date_ts ) >= ((TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), DAY), INTERVAL -7 DAY))) AND ( halfhourly_link_report.date_ts ) < ((TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_ADD(TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(CURRENT_TIMESTAMP(), DAY), INTERVAL -7 DAY), INTERVAL 7 DAY)))))

))

GROUP BY

1,

2,

3

ORDER BY

4 DESC

LIMIT 5000```

3. We also pulled the log file for the `query_id` and found nothing unusual.

```{"duration":"0.000837","sql":"SELECT * FROM `slug` WHERE ((`slug`.`query_id` = 93372) AND (`guid` = '8Q0CXIxpiU2cNmxsTu23MT')) LIMIT 1","h":"192-168-0-91.looker.pod.cluster.local","n":"Skimbit Ltd.","nid":93,"t":"2023-07-06T16:17:08.587+00:00","s":"INFO","rid":"237ca32a882ec2d7","c":"db:looker"}

{"duration":"0.000743","sql":"SELECT * FROM `slug` WHERE ((`guid` = '8Q0CXIxpiU2cNmxsTu23MT') AND (`id` IS NOT NULL))","h":"192-168-0-91.looker.pod.cluster.local","n":"Skimbit Ltd.","nid":93,"t":"2023-07-06T16:17:08.589+00:00","s":"INFO","rid":"237ca32a882ec2d7","c":"db:looker"}

{"duration":"0.001211","sql":"INSERT INTO `slug` (`query_id`, `guid`, `created_at`, `last_fetched`) VALUES (93372, '8Q0CXIxpiU2cNmxsTu23MT', '2023-07-06 16:17:08', '2023-07-06 16:17:08')","h":"192-168-0-91.looker.pod.cluster.local","n":"Skimbit Ltd.","nid":93,"t":"2023-07-06T16:17:08.596+00:00","s":"INFO","rid":"237ca32a882ec2d7","c":"db:looker"}

{"duration":"0.000923","sql":"UPDATE `query` SET `fields` = '[\"halfhourly_link_report.normalized_page_url\",\"publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_domain_name\",\"publisher_domain_metadata.publisher_name\",\"halfhourly_link_report.m_clicks\",\"halfhourly_link_report.m_conversion_rate\",\"halfhourly_link_report.m_order_amount_gbp\",\"halfhourly_link_report.m_sales\",\"halfhourly_link_report.m_total_epc_gbp\"]', `filters` = '{\"halfhourly_link_report.current_date_range\":\"7 days ago for 7 days\"}', `sorts` = '[\"halfhourly_link_report.m_clicks desc\"]', `client_id` = '8Q0CXIxpiU2cNmxsTu23MT' WHERE (`id` = 93372) LIMIT 1","h":"192-168-0-91.looker.pod.cluster.local","n":"Skimbit Ltd.","nid":93,"t":"2023-07-06T16:17:08.609+00:00","s":"INFO","rid":"237ca32a882ec2d7","c":"db:looker"}```

4. We looked at scheduling and observed no bottlenecks.

5. The LookML is generating a fair number of Common Table Expressions but nothing outrageous.

To be quite honest, and I know rendering issues are opaque at best, this one has me stumped. Any insight into how to further troubleshoot or if I'm missing something obvious, please let me know.

Thanks!

Tickets_Subject: Speed up Looker instance
Ticket_Comment_Body:
![Google Cloud](https://vector.my.salesforce.com/servlet/servlet.ImageServer?id=015f4000002r9PP&oid=00Df40000023Flu)



Hello Dion,
 Hope you are doing well!

 Something I can add to the investigation is the post-processing time that Looker could take in order to finish rendering a Look/Dashboard, let me try to explain this point:
 First I have to mention that the _**Queries**_ page and **_query_summary _**doesn't account for the rendering time post query, that is why we could see the queries **_completed _**even when the Dashboard/Look is still loading.

**_Post processing, _**this includes:

- pivoting* (and sorting) for dialects that require in-memory pivoting
- stitching together main query data with total data
- window field post processing (percent of previous and whatnot)
- extents processing (binning used for automagic heatmap)
- sorting (if we need to sort on things like window field data)
- table calcs (if done by the server) + sorting if we need to sort on table calc data
- forecasting
- Custom Visualizations

All of these need to be done on the Looker server/browser itself, so the rendering of the final tile could be delayed to do that post-query processing. So I recommend checking on this too and see (in case we have) if we could reduce them.

Kind Regards,
 Mauro Alejandro
 Looker Support

You can also view and comment on your case by logging into our support portal

Tickets_Subject: Embedded Looker Dashboard no longer sends message events
Tickets_Rating_Comment:
Peakwork is a company located in Germany, and most (not all) of our employees work from Germany. It would be great if a DoiT employee from Europe was assigned by default to our tickets, so working hours match better.

Most optimal would be an input field in the ticket creation "Specify your working hours" or something, so you can implement an automated matching.
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Inside of our product called "Panel", we embedded several Looker Dashboards, so it is easier for our customers to access those. The Frontend is written in Vue, and the embedding works with an iframe and an URL generated by one of our web services.



To improve the user experience, our application interacts in two ways with the embedded dashboards:

1. It adjusts the iframe height to the height required by the Dashboard, so the whole dashboard is visible on the page and there is only one scroll bar
2. When the user navigates to a new Dashboard inside the Dashboard, a back button is shown to safely return to the previous dashboard.



Both features rely on the Looker Dashboard sending message events that are then processed by our code. However, as far as I can tell, no messages at all are sent by the Dashboard.



I attached a screenshot and also our code that is embedding the dashboard. But the code is very similar to what is provided in the documentation https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/embedded-javascript-events. So our assumption is that there is a Bug on Looker side that prevents embedded dashboards to emit message events.



Can you please check if there really is a Bug on Looker side and report it to their developers?

User Interface issues could result from a number of things including Browser's caching and network related concerns. Before attempting to report this issue to the Google Looker team for possible bug, I think the first step would be to verify that this issue isn't a browser-related concern.

These steps below were my intended actions:


1. Confirm if this issue is easily reproducible
2. If it is easily reproducible, perhaps the Customer should attempt the steps in the Incognito Mode of the Google Chrome Browser. This step would help remove doubts relating to caching
3. If the issue is reproducible in the Incognito mode, then perhaps we could gather the HAR[0] files[which would include the logs of each request taken on each steps]
4. Analyzing the logs in the HAR maybe able to provide more insights to where the blockers really are!
5. If not, then perhaps it could indeed be a bug

[0]https://toolbox.googleapps.com/apps/har_analyzer/

Tickets_Subject: Speed up Looker instance
Ticket_Comment_Body:
![Google Cloud](https://vector.my.salesforce.com/servlet/servlet.ImageServer?id=015f4000002r9PP&oid=00Df40000023Flu)



Hello Dion,

 I just got my access to the instance and I have taken a quick look at the System Activity explores. Looks good for the most part.
 However it would be a good idea to look at the Performance recommendations, if those ones mentioned in performance recommendations are used heavily by the users
 https://taboola.cloud.looker.com/dashboards/system__activity::performance_recommendations

 I have checked the instance and java memory as well and it seems to be quiet stable as well.
 However I have noticed that there is a delay in acquiring the connection and also per user query throttling as well, which tends me to believe that there might a few users who would sending a lot of queries into the database at the same time. So it would be good to know how the DB resources are keeping up when you are experiencing slow dashboards or explores to see if its hitting resource limits  or even number of active connections. If DB can hold up and handle more requests, I am wondering if we need to increase the per-user-query limits .

 I have also verified the test explore and dashboard to see if I can reproduce the issue. It looks like the first one took around 10+s to load and I believe it was waiting for the query which took around 5-8s. I have verified this from the backend and it seems to be inline with Async Query Execution.  But in the terms of the page rendering I did not see a huge delay on subsequent page loads (took around 2-3s in both cases ) where queries results are fetched from the cache.

 For next steps:
 1. Could you verify how the backend DB ( guess bigquery is the one which is mostly used ) is holding up in terms of slots available ?
 Also I saw that the connections allowed is 30. Is this something which we should consider increasing ?
 2. Same for --per-user-query-limit as well
 3. I have seen that the mem of the instance is approaching the requested memory but still within limits, and since you are planning to add more users, I can request for a proactive upsize of the instance. But please keep in mind that if DB does not hold up ( we are already seeing throttling issues ), it might actually worsen the performance.

 Hope this helps.
 Feel free to let me know your thoughts on the same

    Thank you !

    Regards,
    Anoop
    Technical Solutions Developer,
    Google Cloud, Toronto
    Availability: 9AM - 5PM ET

Tickets_Subject: Issue with dates and timezone conversions
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi there !



I would have a new question on looker, i'm playing with time fields and it seems there is a slight issue when using the `date_month` and also timezone conversion.

As a reminder with use looker in conjunction with Snowflake.



I can see the following SQL getting generated:



    (
      CONVERT_TIMEZONE(
        'CET',
        'UTC',
        CAST(
          TO_CHAR(
            DATE_TRUNC(
              'month',
              CONVERT_TIMEZONE(
                'UTC',
                'CET',
                CAST(dim_date."DATE"  AS TIMESTAMP_NTZ)
              )
            ),
          'YYYY-MM'
          )
        AS TIMESTAMP_NTZ
        )
      )
    )

The issue that the following SQL does not work.

Indeed the part with the `TO_CHAR` (which is linked to date_month) will typically return `2023-06` for instance, and `CAST('2023-06' AS TIMESTAMP_NTZ)` does not work in Snowflake;



I found a workaround by removing the timezone conversion, but that then limit use cases.

I was wondering if you knew that bug and how to fix that ?



For information i see this happen with dimensions defined as such in lookml :

      dimension_group: start {
        type: time
        description: "Date of start of the subscription"
        datatype: timestamp
        sql: ${TABLE}."DATE_START" ;;
      }

In snowflake the DATE_START is a TIMESTAMP_NTZ column.



Hoping this is something we can fix,



Have a good weekend,

Tickets_Subject: Speed up Looker instance
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Radek,

Google is upgrading the instance and has also requested a HAR file (steps below). The instance upsize is independent of the HAR file. Thank you. /dion

You can record your HTTP session using the Network tab in the Developer Tools in Chrome:

1. Open the Developer Tools from the menu (Menu > More Tools > Developer tools), or by pressing F12 (or Fn-F12) on your keyboard.
2. Click on the Network tab
3. Look for a round button at the top left of the Network tab. Make sure it's red. If it's grey, click it once to start recording.
4. Turn on "Preserve log".
5. You can use the clear button (a circle with a diagonal line through it) right before trying to reproduce the issue to remove unnecessary header information.
6. Reproduce the issue.
7. Save the capture by right-clicking on the grid and choosing "Save as HAR with Content".

Dion Edge (dion@doit-intl.com) // DoiT International (Central Time (US & Canada))

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hey Dion,

Also found again my initial issue !
When querying it seems to behave correctly.
However when building an aggregate table, then for some reason there is an issue :


In cafeyn model you will find an aggregate called `rollup_base_development`

You will also find the dim_subscription and dim_date views where dimensions are defined.
It seems weirdly to be working when in a query, but not when using it with the aggregate table.
If I add convert_tz:no to the concerned dimensions (dim_date.date, start and end in dim_sub) then the problem fixes,

 Please note that your instance is upsized now with an additional node.
 I have verified the infrastructure metrics and everything looks healthy and within limits.

 Also, I have done additional verification on the dashboard below.
 1. Har file from the ticket:
      It seems the most of the time was spend on the query execution and fetching the results. As you have observed query execution just took a little more than 4s. But fetching the results from DB to Looker cache took around 28s. And that seems to be the reason why the loading of explore was slow.

 2. Test on the explore shared below:
      I have run the same test on the explore below. And the results were pretty much the same as above on the first run ( around 30s where most of the time spent on fetching results from DB). I have re-run the query and this time the results were fetched from the cache and page was loaded in less than 5s ( the time spend on content download ). Again tried with a `Clear cache and Refresh`  and pretty the same results ( 30+s ) to load due to fetching results from the DB.

 Could you please let me if this is the same you are seeing as well?
 Are we using a very large dataset. Is it having better response time if the dataset is small ?
 I just did a quick check and when i tried to fetch only 100 rows, it finished under 7s

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Dion - so interestingly i've manage to recreate the steps that generates looker freezing. It's definitely a bug - and it's quite niche. TLDR, closing the frozen tab actually unfreezes all other open looker tabs stuck in loading.



Essentially when you try to create custom group on a dimension, looker generates a query through the grouping modal to get a down list of grouping options. Normally this is fine - but when you try to do it on a field within a view that has a parameter (view level filter) applied to it, this query within the modal seems to take forever, and looker gets stuck in loading. I'll report it to Looker - but it's def onne for the looker nerds...





I think you can go ahead and close the support request

Thanks

# Training, Looker, Google Cloud

## sevenrooms.com (Consolidated Customer, United States)

* * *

request came from
Kwaku Danso
kwaku.danso@sevenrooms.com- please add to ticket

We are reaching out to discuss an issue we are encountering and to explore whether you might have any suggestions.

We have the following setup:
We have two Looker instances (internal and external) running on separate domains: https://sevenrooms.looker.com and https://sevenroomspbl.looker.com.
We maintain a single Git repository used by both instances. Consequently, when we merge into the master branch, a webhook deploys the latest changes to both instances.
There are two Looker models (sevenrooms-internal.model.lkml and sevenrooms-external.model.lkml) where we define our views, explores, and more.
These two instances connect to the same BigQuery tables.
Our application currently inserts every record change into a real-time table named “nightloop_ReservationActual_RealTime_v2”.
We also have another table named “nightloop_ReservationActual_RealTime_Latest” that should store only one version of each record.
At present, we have a Looker view that runs every 3 minutes, merging records from “nightloop_ReservationActual_RealTime_v2” into “nightloop_ReservationActual_RealTime_Latest”.
Upon recent deployment of this merge solution, we observed that both our internal and external instances execute the merge query. We aim to restrict the view’s execution solely to the internal instance, thereby conserving BigQuery slot usage.

Questions:
Could you recommend a method to exclusively run the view on the internal instance?
Additionally, we noticed that although we set the sql_trigger_value to execute every 3 minutes, it occasionally operates with a 5-minute interval or more between executions. Do you have insights into this behavior?

Tickets_Subject: Looker send-to-s3 permission glitch
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Aaron‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Cecilia, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you are getting an "User missing permission to send to specified destination." error.

Have you checked if there has been any changes on the Looker settings and the S3 permissions?

I would suggest to:


- **Check the permissions settings in Looker:** Make sure that the user group in question still has the necessary permissions to send data to S3. You can do this by going to the Admin panel in Looker and checking the permissions for the user group. You can see on this post [1] the error you are having might be due to some changes on the permissions of the user group.


- **Check the S3 bucket permissions**: Make sure that the S3 bucket you are trying to send data to is still accessible and that the permissions have not changed.

[1] https://www.googlecloudcommunity.com/gc/Technical-Tips-Tricks/What-happens-to-a-schedule-of-a-user-after-the-permission-send/ta-p/584471

Please, let me know if this helps.

Tickets_Subject: New column headings with old data
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Prior to July, we were using an old CSAT script, forming the column headings for our data dumps. For the start of July, we updated this CSAT script with new questions, hence the column headings are now different.



When filtering on June only, we used to be able to see the old data with the old script headings in the data dump, and subsequently new data with the new headings when filtering on July onwards.



However, a week ago, we noticed that when filtering on June data, we could see the old data, but under the new script column headings. This creates an issue when trying to download the data from Looker due to the fact the new script is a lot shorter, hence some of the old data will not show as the old script had a lot more questions.



We do not understand why this change has happened, but once checking with other members of the team, they are also unable to see the old script headings with old data.



I have attached two images, one showing July data correctly under the new headings, and one showing when we try to filter on June only.



Please could you advise us on how to get back to being able to see the old data with the old headings?



Best regards,



Annabel

Recently a teammate of ours pointed out that she was having trouble adding dashboards we have in some folders in Looker to her favorites.

According to this Looker documentation we should be able to favorite dashboards from folders as well, but we aren't able to do so: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/finding-content#marking_content_as_a_favorite



Here is the view we see in one of our shared folders with a bunch of dashboards listed. This is the view for my account, I am a Developer role and I have the same experience both when I'm in development mode and when I'm not. This is also happening for Viewer roles. I think there should be a heart icon to the right of each dashboard name, right?

Thank you,

Tickets_Subject: New column headings with old data
Ticket_Comment_Body:
SELECT * FROM (

SELECT *, DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY z___min_rank) as z___pivot_row_rank, RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY z__pivot_col_rank ORDER BY z___min_rank) as z__pivot_col_ordering, CASE WHEN z___min_rank = z___rank THEN 1 ELSE 0 END AS z__is_highest_ranked_cell FROM (

SELECT *, MIN(z___rank) OVER (PARTITION BY "survey_responses.report_group","contact_data.customer_id","contact_data.company","contact_data.title","contact_data.contact_name","contact_data.contact_number1","contact_data.contact_number2","contact_data.email","contact_data.service_date","contact_data.closed_date","data_dump.technician_agent","contact_data.problem_description","data_dump.customer_type","contact_data.fault_code","data_dump.country","data_dump.region","contact_data.service_provider","contact_data.incident_number","data_dump.responsible_entity","data_dump.product_segment","contact_data.serial_number","contact_data.duns_code","contact_data.contract_non_contract","contact_data.us_states_bs_1","contact_data.add01","contact_data.add02","survey_responses.notification_escalation","survey_responses.motivate_escalation","survey_responses.poor_response_escalation","survey_responses.negative_escalation","survey_responses.lead_escalation") as z___min_rank FROM (

SELECT *, RANK() OVER (ORDER BY CASE WHEN z__pivot_col_rank=1 THEN (CASE WHEN "survey_responses.question_reponse" IS NOT NULL THEN 0 ELSE 1 END) ELSE 2 END, CASE WHEN z__pivot_col_rank=1 THEN "survey_responses.question_reponse" ELSE NULL END DESC, "survey_responses.question_reponse" DESC, z__pivot_col_rank, "survey_responses.report_group", "contact_data.customer_id", "contact_data.company", "contact_data.title", "contact_data.contact_name", "contact_data.contact_number1", "contact_data.contact_number2", "contact_data.email", "contact_data.service_date", "contact_data.closed_date", "data_dump.technician_agent", "contact_data.problem_description", "data_dump.customer_type", "contact_data.fault_code", "data_dump.country", "data_dump.region", "contact_data.service_provider", "contact_data.incident_number", "data_dump.responsible_entity", "data_dump.product_segment", "contact_data.serial_number", "contact_data.duns_code", "contact_data.contract_non_contract", "contact_data.us_states_bs_1", "contact_data.add01", "contact_data.add02", "survey_responses.notification_escalation", "survey_responses.motivate_escalation", "survey_responses.poor_response_escalation", "survey_responses.negative_escalation", "survey_responses.lead_escalation") AS z___rank FROM (

SELECT *, DENSE_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY CASE WHEN "english_script_questions.question_number" IS NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END, "english_script_questions.question_number", CASE WHEN "english_script_questions.question_text" IS NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END, "english_script_questions.question_text") AS z__pivot_col_rank FROM (

SELECT

  english_script_questions.QuestionNumber AS [english_script_questions.question_number],

  english_script_questions.QuestionText AS [english_script_questions.question_text],

  CONCAT(survey_responses.ReportYear,'-',survey_responses.ReportMonth) AS [survey_responses.report_group],

  contact_data.CustomerID AS [contact_data.customer_id],

  contact_data.Company AS [contact_data.company],

  contact_data.Title AS [contact_data.title],

  contact_data.ContactName AS [contact_data.contact_name],

  contact_data.ContactNumber1 AS [contact_data.contact_number1],

  contact_data.ContactNumber2 AS [contact_data.contact_number2],

  contact_data.Email AS [contact_data.email],

  contact_data.ServiceDate AS [contact_data.service_date],

  contact_data.ClosedDate AS [contact_data.closed_date],

  data_dump.Technician_Agent AS [data_dump.technician_agent],

  contact_data.ProblemDescription AS [contact_data.problem_description],

  data_dump.CustomerType AS [data_dump.customer_type],

  contact_data.FaultCode AS [contact_data.fault_code],

  data_dump.Country AS [data_dump.country],

  data_dump.Region AS [data_dump.region],

  contact_data.ServiceProvider AS [contact_data.service_provider],

  contact_data.IncidentNumber AS [contact_data.incident_number],

  data_dump.ResponsibleEntity AS [data_dump.responsible_entity],

  data_dump.ProductSegment AS [data_dump.product_segment],

  contact_data.SerialNumber AS [contact_data.serial_number],

  contact_data.DunsCode AS [contact_data.duns_code],

  contact_data.ContractNonContract AS [contact_data.contract_non_contract],

  contact_data.language AS [contact_data.us_states_bs_1],

  contact_data.Add1 AS [contact_data.add01],

  contact_data.Add2 AS [contact_data.add02],

  survey_responses.NotificationEscalation AS [survey_responses.notification_escalation],

  survey_responses.MotivateEscalation AS [survey_responses.motivate_escalation],

  survey_responses.PoorResponseEscalation AS [survey_responses.poor_response_escalation],

  survey_responses.NegativeEscalation AS [survey_responses.negative_escalation],

  survey_responses.LeadEscalation AS [survey_responses.lead_escalation],

  MAX(survey_responses.Response ) AS [survey_responses.question_reponse]

FROM REPORT.MarketIIWarehouse AS survey_responses

INNER JOIN REPORT.ContactData AS contact_data ON contact_data.ContactDataID = survey_responses.SurveyID

INNER JOIN REPORT.DataDump AS data_dump ON data_dump.ContactDataID = survey_responses.SurveyID

INNER JOIN REPORT.EnglishScriptQuestions AS english_script_questions ON survey_responses.ContractID = english_script_questions.ContractID AND

   survey_responses.QuestionNumber = english_script_questions.QuestionNumber

WHERE (((((( CAST(CONCAT(survey_responses.ReportYear, '/',DATEPART(mm,concat('01/',survey_responses.ReportMonth,'/',survey_responses.ReportYear)),'/01') as date) ))) >= (CONVERT(DATETIME, '2023-06-01', 120)) AND ((( CAST(CONCAT(survey_responses.ReportYear, '/',DATEPART(mm,concat('01/',survey_responses.ReportMonth,'/',survey_responses.ReportYear)),'/01') as date) ))) < (CONVERT(DATETIME, '2023-06-30', 120))))) AND (survey_responses.ContractID = 358 )

GROUP BY

  survey_responses.LeadEscalation ,

  survey_responses.MotivateEscalation ,

  survey_responses.NegativeEscalation ,

  survey_responses.NotificationEscalation ,

  survey_responses.PoorResponseEscalation ,

  CONCAT(survey_responses.ReportYear,'-',survey_responses.ReportMonth) ,

  contact_data.ClosedDate ,

  contact_data.Company ,

  contact_data.CustomerID ,

  contact_data.DunsCode ,

  contact_data.ContactName ,

  contact_data.ContactNumber1 ,

  contact_data.ContactNumber2 ,

  contact_data.Email ,

  contact_data.ContractNonContract ,

  contact_data.Title ,

  contact_data.FaultCode ,

  contact_data.IncidentNumber ,

  contact_data.ProblemDescription ,

  contact_data.SerialNumber ,

  contact_data.ServiceDate ,

  contact_data.ServiceProvider ,

  contact_data.Add1 ,

  contact_data.language ,

  contact_data.Add2 ,

  data_dump.Country ,

  data_dump.CustomerType ,

  data_dump.ProductSegment ,

  data_dump.Region ,

  data_dump.ResponsibleEntity ,

  data_dump.Technician_Agent ,

  english_script_questions.QuestionNumber ,

  english_script_questions.QuestionText ) ww

) bb WHERE z__pivot_col_rank <= 16384

) aa

) xx

) zz

 WHERE (z__pivot_col_rank <= 50 OR z__is_highest_ranked_cell = 1) AND (z___pivot_row_rank <= 10 OR z__pivot_col_ordering = 1) ORDER BY z___pivot_row_rank

Tickets_Subject: Handling results from run query when format is set to xlsx
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Dear CRE specialist,

Summary so far:

- My understanding of Looker is limited so this will require a Looker specialist. The customer would like to convert the string value returned by Looker to xlsx and PNG/PDF
- Customer is most likely using [1][2] and, if written in python, they may be able to use `openpyxl` [3] library to generate an xlsx file. Should be able to reference the Python sample code for writing the data [4]. For PNG, might be able to reference [5]
- Public documentation doesn't explicitly state if the response string is base64 encoded

[1]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/reference/looker-api/latest/methods/Query/run_query

Tickets_Subject: Handling results from run query when format is set to xlsx
Ticket_Comment_Body:
This is odd.

So these files show mojibake encoding which is usually the result of mismatched writing systems. My colleague **Gurkomal Rao** suggested the following and I am inclined to agree with him. Please confirm you are using Looker API 4.0.

Have you used the `api_explorer` in Looker and get the same result?


    Customer is most likely using [1][2] and, if written in python, they may be able to use openpyxl [3] library to generate an xlsx file. Should be able to reference the Python sample code for writing the data [4]. For PNG, might be able to reference [5]Public documentation doesn't explicitly state if the response string is base64 encoded [1]: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/reference/looker-api/latest/methods/Query/run_query[2]: https://developers.looker.com/api/explorer/3.1/methods/Query/run_query?sdk=py[3]: https://openpyxl.readthedocs.io/en/stable/[4]: https://github.com/looker-open-source/sdk-codegen/blob/23b3dbfa1761d8b5d6abf6bbaf59318b91082393/examples/python/cloud-function-write-to-bigquery/main.py#L31[5]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/2324133/11860456


Thank you.

/dion

I am using the run query endpoint for which the available documentation is here: https://developers.looker.com/api/explorer/4.0/methods/Query/run_query?sdk=ts (that is the documentation for all looker, not our specific dinacare instance, but the expected request is formatted the same way). I am passing the format option as 'xlsx' and 'png' but I cannot make out how to actually render the returned value as either a .xlsx or .png file. Can you please point me to documentation that would allow me to properly handle the return values from those api calls when I pass in the formats as either xlsx or png?



Thank you,

Lucy

Tickets_Subject: Handling results from run query when format is set to xlsx
Ticket_Comment_Body:
The Looker API documentation is not verbose. The best documentation is in the API Explorer:

https://[company].cloud.looker.com/extensions/marketplace_extension_api_explorer::api-explorer/4.0/methods/Query/run_query?s=run+query

For example:


    // functional SDK syntax is recommended for minimizing browser payloadslet response = await sdk.ok(run_query(sdk, { query_id: '17422', result_format: 'png' }))// monolithic SDK syntax can also be used for Node appslet response = await sdk.ok(sdk.run_query( { query_id: '17422', result_format: 'png' }))

Tickets_Subject: Ability to auto-load dashboard with pre-selected filter values
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi team,



We are trying to solve a problem that we think would greatly help improve the user experience of our customers when they use our embedded dashboards in our vendor portal. As a reminder, we are using the iframe embed option if that helps.



We want both dashboards we have embedded to load automatically upon page load so the user has somewhere to start in terms of viewing data without having to take any initial actions with filters and clicking the load button.

It seems like there is an auto_run setting we can use for this potentially: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/reference/param-lookml-dashboard#auto_run



The problem we are having is we have three different scenarios of how we need this to work:

1. Multi-product dashboard
2. For users with multiple products we want the dashboard to load data for all products from the Product filter option upon page load
3. Single-product dashboard
4. For users with multiple products, we want the dashboard to load data for one of their products, we are not picky which one gets pre-selected but it would be great if we did have a way to choose which one
5. For users with one product, we want the dashboard to load data for that one product





I'm attaching the LookML for each dashboard as well if that helps.



Thank you,

Tickets_Subject: Scatterplot incorrectly rendering custom quadrants
Ticket_Comment_Body:
I have found a bug in the Scatterplot visualisation - specifically in the Custom Quadrants (in the Plot tab of the visualisation settings). Here, you can specify the x and y axis values marking the boundaries of each quadrant. The issue is that when a custom axis value falls outside of the range of values in the data, this boundary value is ignored, and instead the mean for the remaining data is used.

This is problematic and misleading, as in our reporting we have built measures to allow a user to isolate the items in a single quadrant. To apply this functionality, the boundaries are set to specific values (in our case 100). While the items are correctly isolated (our filter measure works as intended), the custom x and y values of 100 fall outside of the min/max range of values in the data, and so default to the mean of the remaining data. I have attached images of this issue to hopefully further clarify.

Our expected behaviour is that when a user filters to only include values in the bottom left quadrant, _only_ the bottom left quadrant should render (i.e. in the examples below, the _entire_ scatterplot should have a red background). The actual behaviour is that four _new_ quadrants are generated within the value boundaries of the bottom left quadrant.

Please can this be updated to follow the expected behaviour.

Thanks

Tickets_Subject: Ability to auto-load dashboard with pre-selected filter values
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Thank you Dion,


As I said today, we have some solutions in place today to make sure our vendors see only their data, but this is inefficient because it loads much more data than is needed and then filters at the end in the outermost WHERE statement. I believe (and correct me if I am wrong) that your solutions from today will suffer from the same issues. I understand that using PDTs will somewhat solve our problem not by getting rid of the inefficiency, but by making it a lot less noticeable. But there are other situations where we would like a dynamic default not only for performance reasons but also for user experience reasons.

The core of the idea is to set a user attribute equal to a list of products (for vendors with only one product, this list will be just the product). I believe the appropriate format would be something like: "Product1","Product2","Product3". We then have the default value on the dashboard filters set to something like.

default_value: "{{ _user_attributes['default_product_names']}}"



We would keep these up to date on our end. I'm not quite clear if we would use the Looker API or something else because of how we handle embedded reports. But that is the crux of the idea. Do you see anything immediately wrong with this idea or any pitfalls we may encounter?

Thank you,

Mark Chlarson

Tickets_Subject: Sum distinct
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello there !



Encountering an issue in on Looker in a view where we use a sum.

Due to a join it seems, looker instead of doing a sum tries a sum distinct.

Except in the sum distinct it then adds the primary key to what we want to sum, and hence the results are completely modified.



Would you be able to join for a call to help as i think this will be way easier to explain?

However i send a screenshot of the issue to explain what is a problem.



Is there a way to prevent the primary key from being summed in ?

We were thinking derived table, but do you think of something else that would be less effort to maintain in the end ?



Thanks in advance.

Hello Kaylin,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Tyler, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand you're having an issue with the line chart's drill feature in some of your Looker dashboards.  They open up correctly upon drilling-down into them, but when you go to download them, the screen goes blank.  I saw the video - thank you.

I'm going to reach out to one of my colleagues with vast Looker experience for some assistance with this.

In the meantime, can you please try clearing your browser's cache/cookies - and/or try a different browser?  Sometimes clearing out cache and/or cookies from a browser (or compatibility issues between browsers) can cause this type of problem in general.

Tickets_Subject: Register OAuth App for Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Also, you can test the registration to see how it performs:

https://developers.looker.com/api/advanced-usage/looker-api-oauth


# Registering an OAuth Client Application
Every OAuth client application that attempts to authenticate into the Looker API using OAuth must first be registered with the Looker instance before Looker will authorize access. To register an OAuth client application:


1. Open the API Explorer on your Looker instance. The default URL used to reach your Looker instance’s API Explorer is `https://<instance_name>:<port>/api-docs/index.html`. The default port for Looker instances hosted on GCP, Microsoft Azure, and instances hosted on AWS that were created on or after 07/07/2020 is `443`. The default port for Looker instances hosted on AWS that were created before 07/07/2020 is `19999`.

2. At the top of the page, enter your API client ID and client secret and click **Log In**. If you do not have an API client ID and client secret, your Looker admin can generate them on the **Users** page in Looker's Admin menu. See the Users documentation page for more information.

3. Use the drop-down menu in the upper right of the page to choose the **4.0 - experimental** version of the API, and click **Reload**.

4. Use the `register_oauth_client_app()` API endpoint to register your OAuth client application with Looker. You can enter the parameters in the API Explorer and click the **Try it out!** button to register the OAuth client application, or use the `register_oauth_client_app()` API endpoint programmatically. The required `register_oauth_client_app()` parameters are:


  - `client_guid`: A globally unique ID for the application
  - `redirect_uri`: The URI where the application will receive an OAuth redirect that includes an authorization code
  - `display_name`: The name of the application that is displayed to users of the application
  - `description`: A description of the application that is displayed to users on a disclosure and confirmation page when a user first logs in from the application

Hello Benjamin‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Renato, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you are having trouble with your git connection in Looker.

Have you tried to sync it manually, by hitting the project's deployment hook?

This article goes over the steps: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/git-options#using_a_deploy_webhook_to_pull_from_a_remote_git_repository

To break it down, you want to open a new tab, paste the following URL but replace the variable `<instance_url>` with your Looker instance host URL, likely something like bluecode.cloud.looker.com (if that's your instance URL):

Tickets_Subject: Cross-project Reporting in Looker (Permission Issues)
Tickets_Rating_Comment: Dion is great to work with.
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Marc‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Birger, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you need to change your Looker connection to connect to a different project and have run into permissions issues.

Your Looker connection uses a service account. To resolve your permissions issues you will need to ensure that service account has been granted the appropriate permissions on the other project.

E.g connecting to another project just means that your BQ jobs will be billed against that project (and, if applicable, use the reservation you've assigned that project to). For that, your service account would need the Job User role [1] (or an equivalent custom role) on that project.

However, to actually access datasets in that project (irrespective of where you're connecting to and running the job), your service account will need permissions to query those datasets (e.g. via the Data Reader role [2])

If you are querying datasets from multiple projects (or from a different project than the one you're connecting to), also make sure you're using fully qualified names (i.e. including the project name) for all tables, views etc that you are referencing in your queries.

Would you mind elaborating what you are trying to achieve, what you've already tried and what results you encountered that were unexpected to you (and why)?

Keep in mind we don't have access to you Looker instance. So you will need to share with us how you've configured your connection.

However, you can grant us read-only permissions on the relevant projects (e.g. the one containing the service accounts and the one you want to connect to where you are getting the permissions issues) so that we can review permissions there.

Regards,
Birger


[1] https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/access-control#bigquery.jobUser
[2] https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/access-control#bigquery.dataViewer


Birger Halfmeier (birger@doit.com) // DoiT International (Melbourne)

Tickets_Subject: 2 issues with Looker API
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi,

We have two ongoing production issues with Looker for a few days already that are impacting the generation of reports in our platform this impacts our customers directly as this is one of the main features we provide.



1. For said reports, we generate temporary looks and try to render them via the API. The rendering of these looks never finishes. We have contacted Looker's support and they restarted our Looker instance and it improved a little, but most of the looks still never finish rendering. I want to emphasize that this is an issue we already had, and Looker's support was able to resolve it in the previous time. (see screenshot from the API where the status is "enqueued_for_render" and never changes to "done")
2. During the generation of these looks, there are some weird queries that Looker runs on our Snowflake instance. Looks like there are the same number of these weird queries as there are filters in these Looks, and the "where" statement in these queries is weird and very general. According to our analysis, these queries do not include the hardcoded filters we have on the looks, so they result in huge table scans, taking forever and blocking the generation of our reports. See the query at the bottom of this message. You can see that it was generated by Looker. We always filter by "realm_id" and by "unique_snapshot_id", but in this query, they are absent from the "where" clause.



These two issues have been impacting our production environment for two days and our production is impacted by this. We are communicating with Looker's support but they don't seem to be able to resolve these issues.



 ![](https://doitintl.zendesk.com/attachments/token/Aa1WIOoDKWWtNvEx0ZviHDkoE/?name=mqbovwct.png)


    WITH assets AS (select a.unique_snapshot_id, a.asset_id, a.id, a.security_score, a.realm_id, a.asset_type,
                    a.exposure_score, a.business_importance_score, a.scan_status, a.is_archived,
                    a.first_seen, a.hosting_type, a.SECURITY_GRADE, a.is_alive, a.is_active, b.grade_weight, a.relatedness, a.last_seen,
                    coalesce(sp.scoring_profile,'v3') as scoring_profile, a.dynamically_resolved
            from assets_looker a
            join realm_parameters b on a.realm_id = b.realm_id
            left join snapshots_parameters sp on (a.realm_id=sp.realm_id and a.unique_snapshot_id=sp.unique_snapshot_id)
            where not is_archived )
      , teams_to_entities AS (SELECT tte.*
              FROM "PUBLIC"."TEAMS_TO_ENTITIES" tte
              INNER JOIN last_teams_updates_v
                    using (unique_update_id)
            )
      , owners_to_entities AS (SELECT ote.*
          FROM "PUBLIC"."OWNERS_TO_ENTITIES" ote
          WHERE lower(ote.owner_name) != concat('__',lower(ote.realm_id))
          )
      , teams_to_owners AS (SELECT tto.unique_update_id, tto.realm_id, tto.update_id, tto.team_id, tto.owner_id, tto.parent_team_id, tto.team_name, tto.is_root
             FROM "PUBLIC"."TEAMS_TO_OWNERS" tto
             INNER JOIN last_teams_updates_v
                    using (unique_update_id)
              )
    SELECT
        locations_to_entities."LOCATION_ID" AS "locations_to_entities.location_id"
    FROM assets
    INNER JOIN teams_to_entities ON (assets."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") = (teams_to_entities."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") and (assets."REALM_ID") = (teams_to_entities."REALM_ID") and assets.ASSET_ID = (teams_to_entities."ENTITY_ID")
    INNER JOIN teams_to_owners ON teams_to_owners.REALM_ID = (teams_to_entities."REALM_ID") and teams_to_owners.UNIQUE_UPDATE_ID = (teams_to_entities."UNIQUE_UPDATE_ID")
          and teams_to_owners.TEAM_ID = (teams_to_entities."TEAM_ID")
    INNER JOIN owners_to_entities ON (owners_to_entities."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") = (teams_to_entities."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") and owners_to_entities.REALM_ID = (teams_to_entities."REALM_ID")
          and owners_to_entities.ENTITY_ID = (teams_to_entities."ENTITY_ID") and owners_to_entities.OWNER_ID = teams_to_owners.OWNER_ID
    LEFT JOIN "LOCATIONS_TO_ENTITIES"
         AS locations_to_entities ON (assets."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") = (locations_to_entities."UNIQUE_SNAPSHOT_ID") and assets.ASSET_ID = (locations_to_entities."ENTITY_ID") and (assets."REALM_ID") = (locations_to_entities."REALM_ID")
    WHERE ((UPPER(( locations_to_entities."LOCATION_ID" )) LIKE UPPER('%') OR UPPER(( locations_to_entities."LOCATION_ID" )) LIKE UPPER('% %'))) AND ( 1=1
                          and assets.scan_status not in ('removed')

    GROUP BY

Tickets_Subject: Editing Schedules in Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Meera, I confirmed editing Schedule can only be accomplished one of three ways as an Admin:


1. Using **Scheduler Plans** page in the Admin panel. There you can reassign yourself as the owner for existing schedules. After reassignment you can then edit as needed and save changes, and if needed, reassign back to the original user.
2. Using the ability to **Sudo** as other users on your Looker instance. Once you Sudo as a given user, you can edit their schedules as needed, save changes and you're all set.
3. Using the update_scheduled_plan() API Endpoint.

Thank you,
/dion

Tickets_Subject: Looker scheduled reports failing due to expired cache
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hey all, we're seeing some Looker scheduled reports failing this morning with the error: "Your scheduled job failed because the results stored in cache were expired or invalid. To resolve, please retry your schedule or wait until the next scheduled job."



Based on some searching, I found this Looker support forum thread that seems to indicate there may be too many/too large reports running but I wanted to see if there's a way to confirm that or if there are other Looker capacity issues/outages happening currently that might be causing this?



The reports that are failing aren't new reports and we haven't seen significant data volume increases, so I'm not sure it's really what's happening here. We're seeing it on 8am, 9am, and 10am central time runs this morning with seemingly no consistency between file extensions or delivery types on the ones that are failing.



We're going to try and stagger the runs for next week but I'd love some assistance confirming that this is the real root cause and not something else we need to be looking into.



I've attached a screenshot of the mix of some of the failed and successful runs. Let me know what you need from me to dig deeper!



Thank you!

Tickets_Subject: Issue with derived table in Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello Freddie‍,

Thank you for contacting DoiT International. My name is Kate, and I was assigned to your case.

I understand that you are seeing multiple derived tables (PDTs) in Looker when you believe there should be only one serving both models? Are these SQL derived or native (LookML) derived?

PDTs can be shared by multiple models so your analysis that there "should" only be one table serving both models is correct. As you are seeing duplicates it is likely that one of the following is happening:

- The datagroup parameters that you have used to persist the PDT are defined differently across your 2 models
- The models use a different connection within the model file
- One of your models has been defined as case sensitive, while the other one isn't. Case sensitivity can affect how a where clause is parsed changing the underlying SQL
- Looker generates a new PDT when it identifies changes in the table's SQL or its triggering parameters, which could be happening due to model-specific settings
- Using the `include: *.view` syntax across all of the models can also cause duplicates. It's recommended to create folders that hold the required views, and then reference the folders directly rather than using the match all wildcard: `include: "/folder_name/*.view.lkml"`
I'd recommend double checking the above to make sure you aren't hitting any of the known reasons for this duplication and if you still cannot see the problem let's arrange a call so we can go through all possible settings.


Please let me know if this answers your questions, and if you need help, I will be happy to assist you.

Sincerely,

Kate Gawron (kate.gawron@doit.com) // DoiT International (UTC)

Tickets_Subject: Looker license question
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello DoIT Team!



We wanted to get on a technical call with Joe and Dion to go over some questions about our Looker licenses and which technical use cases would require separate user licenses. This is specifically about our potential future use case involving API reporting inside our application, not our current Looker platform and license renewal for 2024.



I may have misunderstood, but on the recent call we had with Elaina and the Google team, they mentioned that anyone making use of Looker's semantic layer would require a user license, which we had some questions about.



1. What are the boundaries of when someone needs a Looker license? All three of the below examples make use of Looker's semantic layer, but it doesn't seem that any of them should require additional user licenses outside of the Dina internal users and service accounts who would be creating and configuring the reports and visualizations returning the data.



- Scheduled Looker reports to external e-mail addresses (for making operational reporting available to our customers) make use of the semantic layer, but those users don't require any additional user licensing, right?



- If we have a dedicated application service account licensed as a Standard user that has an API key assigned. Using that API key, Dina's application allows Dina users to access data from our Looker API, with filters set by the Dina application to apply Dina's RLS logic to the query. Excluding the service account that's assigned the API key, this usage wouldn't require any additional user licensing , right?



- If we exposed a Look with "Public Access" enabled, for example a collection of useful healthcare marketing information that might convince leads to reach out to our sales team, this usage wouldn't require any additional use licensing, right?



We'd love to get on a call to better understand what we can and can't do with our existing licenses to make sure we're handling things correctly, thanks!

Tickets_Subject: Issue configuring batch TTL in ExecutionConfig
Tickets_Rating_Comment: Thanks so much to the team for helping us quickly dig into our GCP issues and navigate their confusing documentation!
Ticket_Comment_Body:
The root cause is an outdated Pypi package `google-cloud-dataproc`:


- All Composer images, including latest, uses `google-cloud-dataproc` 5.7.0. This has a bug because even gcloud commands are affected [1]. Within the same thread, a user stated upgrading the version of Cloud SDK resolved the issue. PyPi package has version 5.8.0 available
- Manually upgrading to 5.8.0 resolved the error. `TTL` needs to be set in seconds otherwise the API returns an error:


    "environment_config": {  "execution_config": {  "ttl": "21600s"  }  }



- Seeing the latest reply, they are using another providers package so they will have to resolve some other package conflicts manually. Testing within my environment returned:


    Failed to install Python packages. sqlalchemy-spanner 1.6.2 has requirement google-cloud-spanner>=3.12.0, but you have google-cloud-spanner 1.19.3.  Check the Cloud Build log at https://console.cloud.google.com/cloud-build/builds/c5ecbd04-dede-4450-86dc-91a74da412a9?project=21314870745 for details. For detailed instructions see https://cloud.google.com/composer/docs/troubleshooting-package-installation


[1]: https://stackoverflow.com/q/77624632/11860456

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi David,

Just as a final note, we found that `google-cloud-dataproc` adds the `ttl` field in version 5.4.0 [1] so anything below 5.3.0 [2] should always produce the error. Unfortunately, `apache-airflow-providers-google==8.8.0` uses a very old version of the Dataproc client library because of dependencies that rely on an old version of protobuf. Upgrading to 5.4.0 should lead to conflicts similar to [3].

Using new versions is generally recommended, but, it might not always be feasible within certain environments since it could cause other sections of your code to fail. For this reason, a temporary solution can be to leverage the `KubernetesPodOperator` [4] to create a customized pod. By attaching a custom image (with the Dataproc Client library version >=5.4.0 installed),  you can have the pod execute a script containing Dataproc client library [5] code, instead of using Airflow operators.

[1]: https://github.com/googleapis/python-dataproc/blob/45a42460040b089b9be63695365326162e26a6ee/google/cloud/dataproc_v1/types/shared.py#L208
[2]: https://github.com/googleapis/python-dataproc/blob/51674369331d8b3167d594db1976b2a33f57d3a7/google/cloud/dataproc_v1/types/shared.py#L168
[3]:

    google-cloud-vision 1.0.2 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-videointelligence 1.16.3 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-translate 1.7.2 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-texttospeech 1.0.3 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-speech 1.3.4 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-spanner 1.19.3 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-secret-manager 1.0.2 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-language 1.3.2 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-dlp 1.0.2 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-bigtable 1.7.3 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.google-cloud-bigquery 2.34.4 requires protobuf<4.0.0dev,>=3.12.0, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible.apache-airflow-providers-google 8.8.0 requires protobuf<=3.20.0, but you have protobuf 4.25.1 which is incompatible

[4]: https://airflow.apache.org/docs/apache-airflow-providers-cncf-kubernetes/stable/operators.html#kubernetespodoperator
[5]: https://cloud.google.com/python/docs/reference/dataproc/latest/google.cloud.dataproc_v1.services.batch_controller.BatchControllerClient#google_cloud_dataproc_v1_services_batch_controller_BatchControllerClient_create_batch

Tickets_Subject: Create SFTP connection with
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hello,

Based on the information you've provided, it seems like you're trying to set up an SFTP connection to a remote server using AWS Transfer Family. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this:

1. Open the AWS Transfer Family console at [https://console.aws.amazon.com/transfer/](https://console.aws.amazon.com/transfer/).
2. In the left navigation pane, choose **Connectors**, then choose **Create connector**.
3. Choose **SFTP** for the connector type to create an SFTP connector, and then choose **Next**.
4. In the **Connector configuration** section, provide the following information:
   - For the **URL**, enter the URL for the remote SFTP server. In your case, it would be `sftp://omnitailfeeds.hostedftp.com:22`.
   - For the **Access role**, choose the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) role to use. This role should have read and write access to the parent directory of the file location that's used in the `StartFileTransfer` request.
5. In the **SFTP Configuration** section, provide the following information:
   - For **Connector credentials**, from the dropdown list, choose the name of a secret in AWS Secrets Manager that contains the SFTP user's private key or password. You must create a secret and store it in a specific manner. For details, see [Store an existing secret for use with an SFTP connector](#sftp-connector-secret-procedure).
   - **Trusted host keys** – Paste in the public portion of the host key that is used to authenticate the user to the external server, or choose **Add trusted host key** to add an additional key.
6. After you have confirmed all of your settings, choose **Create connector** to create the SFTP connector.

Please note that the IAM role you use should have the necessary permissions to access the S3 bucket where your CSV files are stored. Also, the secret you create in AWS Secrets Manager should contain the username and password for the SFTP server.

If you follow these steps and still encounter issues, a specialist will be assigned to help with this request.

For more information, you can refer to the AWS documentation on [Creating SFTP connectors](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/transfer/latest/userguide/create-connector.html).

Keywords for further search: AWS Transfer Family, SFTP connector, AWS Secrets Manager, IAM role, StartFileTransfer

Additional questions for troubleshooting: 
- What is the exact error message you're receiving when trying to set up the connection via Looker?
- Have you verified the username and password for the SFTP server?
- Does the IAM role have the necessary permissions to access the S3 bucket and the Secrets Manager?
- Have you stored the SFTP server credentials correctly in AWS Secrets Manager?

Eric,

I suspect there is a bug fix in this 23.20 feature:


    Quick Layout for dashboard editors has been added behind the dashboard_layout_accelerator feature flag, which is available to customers in preview. Users can now move dashboard tiles to the left or the right side and also resize them to standard sizes. Fill out the Looker Dashboard Layout Accelerator Preview Sign Up form to sign up for the preview.


It is not uncommon to fix small, related bug with new features. Now that I've seen the extent of the cropping and we replicated the error in Firefox this has the hallmarks of bug. Unfortunately, i have not found reported bugs exactly like yours but a fair number of similar PDF cropping issues, just not across all rendered PDFs.

Thank you.

Tickets_Subject: Looker does not remove all artifacts from old Looker Action Hubs
Ticket_Comment_Body:
I found the issue.

This is a user error.

The Looker Action Hub server has a `ACTION_HUB_BASE_URL` environment variable. This needs to also change each time the proxy hostname changes.

This is sent back to Looker on the initial connection.

We can close this now.

Ticket_Comment_Body:

Josie, Elena, and I are going to meet and make sure we're all on the same page. As for increasing the horsepower on the monthly APIs, Looker just needs to increase your resource allocation. You're probably not on a cluster at the moment and but they would. mostly move your instance to a hefty cluster. This probably comes with a license  change and Elena should be able to answer that (I'll ask when I meet with her). But the mechanics are pretty pedestrian.

Thanks!
/dion

Hi DoiT International team,

I found a similar case where users were able to download the report in the CHROMIUM 98 version rather than when using the latest versions.

As of now, Looker rendering supports Chrome versions up to and including Chrome 114. Looker versions earlier than Looker 23.10 support up to Chrome version 109. We can check for this information in the release notes: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/release-notes

Let me know if by downgrading Chromium to 98 version works fine.

Regards,
Carlos

Tickets_Subject: Inconsistent last login report in Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Dion,



Please see below the SQL we've used to create a report.



SELECT

  user.id AS `user.id`,

  CONCAT((CONVERT(user.first_name USING utf8mb4)), ' ', (CONVERT(user.last_name USING utf8mb4))) AS `user.name`,

    (DATE(user.CREATED_AT )) AS `user.created_date`,

    (DATE(user_facts.LAST_UI_LOGIN_AT )) AS `user_facts.last_ui_login_date`,

  user_facts.last_ui_login_credential_type AS `user_facts.last_ui_login_credential_type`,

    (CASE WHEN user_facts.is_verified_looker_employee THEN 'Yes' ELSE 'No' END) AS `user_facts.is_looker_employee`,

    (CASE WHEN user.is_disabled THEN 'Yes' ELSE 'No' END) AS `user.is_disabled`,

  user.email AS `user.email`,



      group_concat(DISTINCT role.name )

      AS `role.role_list`,

    (DATE(MAX(

      CONVERT(history.CREATED_AT USING utf8mb4)

      ))) AS `history.most_recent_query_date`

FROM user AS user

LEFT JOIN user_facts ON user.id = user_facts.user_id

LEFT JOIN user_facts_role ON user.id = user_facts_role.user_id

LEFT JOIN role ON user_facts_role.role_id = role.id

LEFT JOIN history ON user.id = history.user_id

WHERE (CONCAT((CONVERT(user.first_name USING utf8mb4)), ' ', (CONVERT(user.last_name USING utf8mb4))) ) IS NOT NULL

GROUP BY

  1,

  2,

  3,

  4,

  5,

  6,

  7,

  8

ORDER BY

  9 DESC

LIMIT 600



Cheers,

Radek

Ticket_Comment_Body:
Hi Dion,



Seems like indeed this query cannot be run in SQL runner, since there is no access to the internal Looker database. You need to recreate the report in the following way.



Steps to replicate:

1. Navigate to Looker hope page
2. Click Explore
3. Within explores, view the sub category of System Activity
4. At the bottom of System Activity (for me at least) there is an explore called User
5. In the User explore, select the following dimensions from three different views:

- User:
- Created Date -> Date
- Email
- ID
- Is Disabled (yes/no)
- Name
- User Facts:
- Last Attempted UI Login Date -> Date (this is the dimension causing the discrepancy I believe)
- UI Sessions -> Last Attempted UI Login Credential Type
- User Permissions -> Is Looker Employee
- User Role:
- Role List

Tickets_Subject: Inconsistent last login report in Looker
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Radek, Sean, et al.

Good news:


    Thanks for reaching out to Looker support. I see that you found a discrepancy for the last login information for the user anoopjoseph@google.com between what is reported in System Activity and what is reported in the Admin - Users panel. Since this user is a Looker employee, they most likely logged in through support access , and it looks like these logins are not counted in the reporting on the Admin - Users panel. In general I would recommend using System Activity as the source of truth. I won't be able to share the full System Activity LookML model, but I will look for the specific SQL query that we run against the internal database for populating the "Never Logged In" value in the Admin - Users panel and send it to you so that you can compare the queries directly.Best,Chris


and...


    It looks like the new Admin - Users panel runs the following API call to populate the list of users and their information.Request from 127.0.0.1, GET /api/4.0/users/search, {"embed_user":"false","fields":"id,email,first_name,last_name,role_ids,group_ids,credentials_email,credentials_google,credentials_saml,credentials_oidc,credentials_api,credentials_api3,credentials_ldap,credentials_embed,display_name,is_disabled,is_iam_admin,can","page":"1","per_page":"25","sorts":"first_name asc,last_name asc"}Each credential type listed in the API call, such as credentials_email, has its own corresponding internal db table, so we run separate queries against each table like this:SELECT * FROM `credentials_email` WHERE (`credentials_email`.`user_id` IN ([list of user ids]))The results from these queries include the last login date for the user, which is in a last_login_at field in each credentials table. However, the credentials for users who log in via support auth access are stored in the credentials_looker_openid table, and credentials_looker_openid is not one of the credential types requested in the query params of the API call. Therefore, we do not retrieve the last login date for support auth access logins.It seems like we should be including every credentials table in the API call we run for this page so that we are accurately reporting the last login date for every listed user, so I'll let the engineering team know about this issue. In the meantime, as I mentioned previously, I would recommend using System Activity to verify the last login dates for all users. You may also be able to get more information on support access logins from the Support Access Login dashboard: https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/admin-panel-general-support-access#support_access_auditLet me know if there is any other information that would be helpful.Best,ChrisGoogle Cloud Support


Thank you.
/dion

Tickets_Subject: [gCRE] Architecture Review, Looker - Google Cloud for autotrader.co.uk
Ticket_Comment_Body:
Good morning, David, et al.

This afternoon I would like to discuss a few approaches to the problem. A colleague in New York from [Spectacles.dev](https://www.spectacles.dev/) made these presentations about a year ago and I think they lay the ground for a useful, albeit non-trivial solution. If you have the time all of his Looker webinars are really quite helpful.

How To Fix Your LookML Project Structure

The first three recommendations are:


1. Keep your model files unchanged from their Create View from Table auto-generation by storing them separately .
2. Centralize edits of view  files using Refinements.
3. Store Explores in their own dedicated files.

Think of refactoring your single massive LookML project like replacing your fence a few boards at a time.

The second part of this strategy involves extensive use of Groups (instead of roles) at the permission level and [access_grant.

Robust Access Control And Permission Management

Assuming groups are already inherited at the database, we can assert they will still be useful in Looker. At the model level we can use `access_grant` for granular  requirements (in lieu of OAuth). Here are the Best Practices for Groups.)(https://cloud.google.com/looker/docs/best-practices/how-to-manage-users-with-groups)

Additionally, there are two tools that I know will make this more economical in execution:

1. looker-open-source The Admin Power Pack is a tool for Looker administrators to accomplish certain management tasks more efficiently. It is a Looker add-on application built using the Looker extension framework. Currently it offers utilities for extended functionality in two main areas: schedules and users.

2. Looker Deployer (aka 'ldeploy') is a command line tool to help move Looker objects across instances. This includes Content (Looks, Dashboards, entire Spaces, etc.), Boards and Connections, and Authentication.
+ https://github.com/looker-open-source/looker_deployer
+ https://github.com/looker-open-source/looker_deployer
 https://github.com/looker-open-source/looker_deployer

Regards,
/dion

Dion Edge (dion@doit.com) // DoiT International (Central Time (US & Canada))
